Subject: [sfraves] Newsom wants club promoters to get permits, more cops, etc. to stem nightclub related violence

>From The Examiner:

Responding to a recent spike in violent crimes in and around San Francisco's popular nightclubs, Mayor Gavin Newsom announced new legislation Thursday intended to make the venues safer.

Under the proposed legislation - to be introduced by Supervisor Sophie Maxwell at Tuesday's Board of Supervisors meeting - it would be illegal to loiter within 10 feet of a club for more than three minutes between the hours of 9 p.m. and 3 a.m.

People smoking or waiting for a bus or taxi would be exempted, and police would have to issue a warning before citing a loiterer.

The legislation also would require promoters who hold two or more events at nightclubs within any given year to obtain a permit.

As it is now, the mayor said, "fly-by-night" promoters come and go without anybody keeping track of them. Permits would enable the Police Department and other city agencies to know who is responsible for an event in the case of a security breach or health violation.

In addition, the legislation would grant emergency powers to the director of the city Entertainment Commission to suspend permits for safety or noise violations. If a promoter planned an event for Friday and Saturday nights and the Friday night party got out of hand, the director could unilaterally cancel the Saturday night event.

Finally, the legislation would require nightclubs with extended hours - usually from 2 to 6 a.m. - to produce security plans to be approved by the director of the Entertainment Commission.

Four homicides occurred outside nightclubs in 2007, and there have been two more this year. Fifteen percent of all assaults in the city take place in or around nightclubs, the mayor's office said.

The Mayor's Office of Criminal Justice convened a special meeting in January on the issue, and representatives from 250 live music venues, nightclubs and comedy clubs attended and helped craft the legislation.

The announcement Thursday was similar to one made by the mayor in the fall of 2006, when he outlined new safety crackdowns along the Broadway corridor in North Beach, where fights, muggings and underage drinking were all increasing.

At that time, he announced there would be extra police officers patrolling the neighborhood. Also, the Sheriff's Department would have a van stationed there to transport people who were arrested to the County Jail, and authorities would visit nightclubs to ensure that alcohol laws and noise ordinances were being obeyed.

"We're very successful there, but it's just very labor-intensive," Newsom said, noting that the Broadway efforts will continue but that the new legislation would bolster the city's efforts to crack down on violence.

Brit Hahn, owner of City Nights and Club Envy, both in the South of Market neighborhood, and Rouge in North Beach, said he supports the new legislation.
He said more people are coming to his clubs - not to pay the cover charge and party inside, but to hang out on the street outside or in adjacent alleys. He said they break into cars, start fights and bother people waiting in line.

"The city and the industry need tools to deal with what's been a growing problem in the past few years," he said.

E-mail Heather Knight at hknight@sfchronicle.com. 

http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2008/02/29/BALDVB0HH.DTL&type=printable

Subject: [sfraves] NRR: Wanted: First Time Voters (fwd)

Info from a SF non-commercial station, KALW



---------- Forwarded message ----------
Date: Sat, 1 Mar 2008 11:50:05 -0800
From: Rose Aguilar <rosea@storiesinamerica.org>
To: undisclosed-recipients:  ;

Hi all,

On Monday, I'm doing a radio show about first time voters. For younger
voters, how does it feel to vote for the first time? For older voters,
what got you to the polls? And what will it take to engage these new
voters in the political process after the election? Will they stay
involved?

We're hoping to hear from first time voters of all ages.

We'll also be speaking with a few of the students from Texas who
walked 7.3 miles to vote a few weeks ago:
http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/politics/5552259.html

The show airs from 11 am - noon PST this Monday on KALW 91.7 FM. You
can also listen online at: http://www.yourcallradio.org/

Please send this to friends, family, or co-workers who are voting for
the first time. We'll also take calls from people who want to talk
about their first time voting experience.

Thanks,
Rose

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Jump!  Tonight at Shine - 2/29



Ended up not being able to get to the after, sorry I missed you guys.

So, I saw a couple of folks there that I recognized and got some very
positive feedback but I don't know all your emails, so a very public
thank you to everyone who came.  Got a few new folks who lamented "lack"
of techno(as in, they didn't know about most of the parties!), I happily
mentioned a couple of the other parties and think our audience has expanded
a bit, so maybe instead of 30 techno fans there are 33 now. ;)

Oh, and I'm proud to say I got one memorable criticism saying I need to
book more electro-house, so I must be doing something right. ;)  I think
she stumbled across to club six for hip-hop, and wish her well in life. =)

Definitely reaffirms my feeling that, while we don't want to intentionally
poach each other, there's plenty of room for all of us even with multiple
yumminess on the same night, we all just need to get better at what we're
doing and enjoy the return of hopping. =)

Ray

Subject: Re: [sfraves] 3/29 and comprehensive collision insurance

promoters claiming dates has always been around its just never been 
said. but i think the confusion arises when we all don't know what is 
happening and nobody promotes in advance. like if i was booking local 
talent techno night i wouldn't for sure book it on the same night as my 
friend's parties. i look at it this way,  if you were throwing an event 
that you tried REALLY hard  to just break even and its in the east bay, 
and then at the same time, there were two parties YOU would rather be at 
in the city on the same night.. it kind of tends to piss you off. `;P

in regards to terry's wiki calendar... i'm not sure it will work, -as a 
wiki. you would need a form and a living person to actually approve a 
posting. a human being with a yes no system would work.. the 'robots' 
aren't that great at managing websites just yet.  i like the idea of the 
calendar starting up again mostly because i don't have to sit around 
here waiting for a great party to show up and listen to NRRs all day. 
not that i don't enjoy the art of lock bumping (explains why so many 
kyptonite locks are still around locked to things) or you guys company, 
i just would like a quick reference guide. also i remember in high 
school when i would print the sfr calendar out and just scan the thing 
over and over and drool at the possibilities. oooh dutch, simon and tony 
[homer simpson drooling noises].. a single line of info with not too 
much mention of anything....oooh looks like an underground!!

the calendar would assist people in knowing what and who the competition 
was on a particular night.  if it was a  skills massive you were going 
up against or if it was a party your friend who forgot to flyer you for. 
also i think i'm missing alot of great parties out there. it would be 
nice to know who was doing what.. like a veritable 'who's who.' if there 
were up and coming DJs you could see them start to creep up on more 
calendar entries and you could investigate them.. or if there were radio 
shows like 'epiphany of sound' people could look them up easier.

my opinion of why the calendar died i think stems from the time when 
cops were pretty wise to the sfr calendar and people were paranoid about 
lurkers seeing open information on the web.. not to say it still doesn't 
happen in this forum but having a calendar with some security might be 
in order. or two calendars. one open and one secret..? maybe that was a 
dilemma that was never solved in the early incarnation of the calendar..

in regards to there being SO many people into EDM here.. well no, there 
aren't. not the ones that would come out that aren't jaded by the scene. 
it takes alot of motivation and persuasion for somebody to leave their 
house and take up car keys and drive to lodi for an outdoor party these 
days. so if you're trying to win a particular crowd and you know your 
audience pretty well, they won't go to your party if you're trying to 
rep the local scene when they know some headliner they'll never see 
again is in town. my experience tells me that this scene (i.e. the 
people that actually come out) is usually at either one party a week or 
another and that's the way its always been. that is, unless the parties 
are in really far off places in the bay.

end of line
sean.

Marco wrote:
> The idea of promoters "claiming dates" is kind of preposterous to me. 
> It's always annoyed me when I'd attempt to throw an event and hear 
> people bitch about it "competing" with other promoters events.
>
> I mean...if you don't want me throwing an event that competes, why 
> don't you book me so I have something else going on that night? No 
> booking for your party? Expect some healthy competition! There is an 
> entire city with SCADS of people who listen to EDM here to appease, 
> there is no good reason for people not to do whatever the fuck they 
> want w/o regard for other people's events.

Farmer, rave organizer fined for disorderly conduct
By LAWRENCE SUSSMAN
lsussman@journalsentinel.com
Posted: Feb. 26, 2008

Port Washington - An Ozaukee County circuit judge Monday found a Town  
of Belgium farmer and an event organizer who held a rave party on a 90- 
acre dairy farm in September guilty of disorderly conduct.

Farmer Dennis W. Dahm has held outdoor parties at his farm for at  
least five years. During Labor Day weekend last year, the Ozaukee  
County Sheriff's Department closed down the party after two nights and  
cited Dahm and one of the organizers, Christopher A. Grant, on  
suspicion of disorderly conduct.

Last fall, the Town of Belgium sued Dahm, asking that the parties be  
declared public nuisances and permanently banned. That case is pending.

During Monday's trial, James J. Manders and Barbara Graham, who live  
about a half-mile from Dahm's farm, testified that "rhythmic thumping"  
from the party kept them awake after midnight Sept. 1.

They said a "pounding electric kind of music" rattled their windows,  
and disc jockeys at the party shouting "let's rock the (expletive)  
house" could be heard by their granddaughter in their house, which had  
the windows closed and the air conditioning on.

"If it's sufficient to rattle the windows half a mile away, that's as  
disorderly as you can get," Circuit Judge Tom R. Wolfgram said. "There  
was a certain amount of vulgarity going on. . . . It did tend to  
create a disturbance in their home. Their granddaughter heard  
persistent noise."

Dahm did not attend the trial. Wolfgram found him guilty by default  
and fined him $186.

Wolfgram found Grant, 26, of Milwaukee, guilty of two counts of  
disorderly conduct, and fined him $186 on each count.

After the trial, Grant said he has no plans to hold a rave party at  
the Dahm farm this year. A rave party is an all-night dance in which  
disc jockeys and other performers use synthesizers, drums and  
electronic music equipment.

In the lawsuit, the town is seeking a permanent injunction that would  
stop "musical festivals" from being held on Dahm's farm.

Dahm could not be reached for comment.


apollo@speakeasy.org

Tribenet:   http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k

Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

Don't these farmers grow anything besides beets?

The beet is the most intense of vegetables. The radish, admittedly, is the 
more feverish, but the fire of the radish is a cold fire, the fire of 
discontent not passion. Tomatoes are lusty enough, yet there runs through 
tomatoes an undercurrent of frivolity. Beets are deadly serious.

- Tom Robbins, Jitterbug Perfume

Best,

Peter

On Sun, Mar 2, 2008 at 8:23 PM, Apollo <apollo@speakeasy.org> wrote:

> Farmer, rave organizer fined for disorderly conduct
> By LAWRENCE SUSSMAN
> lsussman@journalsentinel.com
> Posted: Feb. 26, 2008
>
> Port Washington - An Ozaukee County circuit judge Monday found a Town
> of Belgium farmer and an event organizer who held a rave party on a 90-
> acre dairy farm in September guilty of disorderly conduct.
>
> Farmer Dennis W. Dahm has held outdoor parties at his farm for at
> least five years. During Labor Day weekend last year, the Ozaukee
> County Sheriff's Department closed down the party after two nights and
> cited Dahm and one of the organizers, Christopher A. Grant, on
> suspicion of disorderly conduct.
>
> Last fall, the Town of Belgium sued Dahm, asking that the parties be
> declared public nuisances and permanently banned. That case is pending.
>
> During Monday's trial, James J. Manders and Barbara Graham, who live
> about a half-mile from Dahm's farm, testified that "rhythmic thumping"
> from the party kept them awake after midnight Sept. 1.
>
> They said a "pounding electric kind of music" rattled their windows,
> and disc jockeys at the party shouting "let's rock the (expletive)
> house" could be heard by their granddaughter in their house, which had
> the windows closed and the air conditioning on.
>
> "If it's sufficient to rattle the windows half a mile away, that's as
> disorderly as you can get," Circuit Judge Tom R. Wolfgram said. "There
> was a certain amount of vulgarity going on. . . . It did tend to
> create a disturbance in their home. Their granddaughter heard
> persistent noise."
>
> Dahm did not attend the trial. Wolfgram found him guilty by default
> and fined him $186.
>
> Wolfgram found Grant, 26, of Milwaukee, guilty of two counts of
> disorderly conduct, and fined him $186 on each count.
>
> After the trial, Grant said he has no plans to hold a rave party at
> the Dahm farm this year. A rave party is an all-night dance in which
> disc jockeys and other performers use synthesizers, drums and
> electronic music equipment.
>
> In the lawsuit, the town is seeking a permanent injunction that would
> stop "musical festivals" from being held on Dahm's farm.
>
> Dahm could not be reached for comment.
>
>
> apollo@speakeasy.org
>
> MySpace:  http://www.myspace.com/DJApollo
>
> Tribenet:  http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k
>
> Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org
>
> House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm
>
>
>
> "No wonder kids grow up crazy," the midget says. "A cat's cradle is
> nothing but a bunch of X's between somebody's hands, and little kids
> look and look and look at all those X's..."
> "And?"
> "No damn cat, and no damn cradle."
> -Kurt Vonnegut
>
> "Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of
> the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will
> gradually become visible."
> -Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"
>
>
>

> On Sun, Mar 2, 2008 at 8:23 PM, Apollo <apollo@speakeasy.org> wrote:
>
>> Farmer, rave organizer fined for disorderly conduct
>> By LAWRENCE SUSSMAN
>> lsussman@journalsentinel.com
>> Posted: Feb. 26, 2008
>>
>> Port Washington - An Ozaukee County circuit judge Monday found a Town
>> of Belgium farmer and an event organizer who held a rave party on a  
>> 90-
>> acre dairy farm in September guilty of disorderly conduct.
>>
>> Farmer Dennis W. Dahm has held outdoor parties at his farm for at
>> least five years. During Labor Day weekend last year, the Ozaukee
>> County Sheriff's Department closed down the party after two nights  
>> and
>> cited Dahm and one of the organizers, Christopher A. Grant, on
>> suspicion of disorderly conduct.
>>
>> Last fall, the Town of Belgium sued Dahm, asking that the parties be
>> declared public nuisances and permanently banned. That case is  
>> pending.
>>
>> During Monday's trial, James J. Manders and Barbara Graham, who live
>> about a half-mile from Dahm's farm, testified that "rhythmic  
>> thumping"
>> from the party kept them awake after midnight Sept. 1.
>>
>> They said a "pounding electric kind of music" rattled their windows,
>> and disc jockeys at the party shouting "let's rock the (expletive)
>> house" could be heard by their granddaughter in their house, which  
>> had
>> the windows closed and the air conditioning on.
>>
>> "If it's sufficient to rattle the windows half a mile away, that's as
>> disorderly as you can get," Circuit Judge Tom R. Wolfgram said.  
>> "There
>> was a certain amount of vulgarity going on. . . . It did tend to
>> create a disturbance in their home. Their granddaughter heard
>> persistent noise."
>>
>> Dahm did not attend the trial. Wolfgram found him guilty by default
>> and fined him $186.
>>
>> Wolfgram found Grant, 26, of Milwaukee, guilty of two counts of
>> disorderly conduct, and fined him $186 on each count.
>>
>> After the trial, Grant said he has no plans to hold a rave party at
>> the Dahm farm this year. A rave party is an all-night dance in which
>> disc jockeys and other performers use synthesizers, drums and
>> electronic music equipment.
>>
>> In the lawsuit, the town is seeking a permanent injunction that would
>> stop "musical festivals" from being held on Dahm's farm.
>>
>> Dahm could not be reached for comment.
>>
>>

Please tune in to KZSU by listening to 90.1 in the Bay Area or pointing
your web browser to http://kzsulive.stanford.edu.

If you're interested in guest appearing on any of our shows
or having a mix featured contact us using our email addresses
or: electronicadjs@kzsu.stanford.edu

This week we'll have ticket give aways for the ForwardSF and
Dirtybird 3rd Anniversary parties happening in San Francisco
on Saturday, March 8th. Be sure to tune in!

We're getting plans together for the Spring Equinox 24 hour
electronic music marathon. More details soon!

Big Love Show with Jack Wang - Mondays 3PM-6PM PST (11PM UTC)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

This week Jack is proud to host DJ Adnan from ForwardSF joined by Guada
from Mexico and Sayaka from Japan. More information about Adnan and
this weekend's party can be found at:
http://www.forwardsf.com/

The mix starts up in a few hours with techno, house, and other electronica.


Eclektronik Groove w/ Holt Sorenson - Mon->Tues 12AM-3AM PST (8AM UTC)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

Holt will be hosting DJ Monaco, an up and coming DJ that recently
moved to the SF Bay Area from the east coast. More infos on
DJ Monaco:
http://www.myspace.com/nathanmonaco


Epiphany of Sound with J.C. - Thursday 9AM-12PM PST (5PM UTC)
-------------------------------------------------------------------------

After 14 years, DJ J.C.'s techno/house/electronica showcase has
garnered much attention and devotion. Like most folks at Stanford's
radio station, he's a volunteer, proving that his motivation isn't
a paycheck; it's his passion to share his interest in one of music's
most eclectic genres. With his conversational style, inclusion of
producers and musicians from both the local & international scene,
and his stewardship of the station's 24-hour marathons during
Solstices and Equinoxes, it's no wonder that DJ J.C has made a
connection with listeners in a very crowded market. Catch his live
broadcasts or listen to the previous week's program at underheard.org.

J.C. will email this week if he has an update on any guests.

Thanks for your support!!!

--
Holt Sorenson/Eclektronik Groove
hso@hsomusic.com
hsomusic.com - myspace.com/hsomusic
KZSU (kzsulive.stanford.edu) show on Mon Nite/Tues Morn. 12-3AM

Subject: [sfraves] BSP: Yuri's Night 2008 @ Moffett Field

Hey guys, it's happening again this year, come check it out
it'll be fun!

http://www.yurisnightbayarea.com

Taking place at Hangar 211, NASA Ames Reserch Center

More Than a Festival...

Come to Yuri's Night Bay Area to kick back, celebrate, and 
dance, but also be ready to learn, interact, and think! You 
could think of Yuri's Night as a fusion of a technology expo, a 
Maker Faire, an art exhibition, and a music festival, all rolled into one.

Yuri's Night Bay Area 2008 includes:

     * A world-class lineup of musical artists, ranging from the 
ethereal breakbeat sounds of Tipper to Telstar, with Phil Lesh 
of the Grateful Dead.
     * A mind-expanding series of speakers, from NASA scientists 
to video-game designers to Bay Area entrepreneurs.
     * Live performances of all kinds, from dance and acrobatics 
by Capacitor to aerial demonstrations featuring Yuri-Gagarin-era 
aerobatic aircraft.
     * Dozens of art and science installations, including 
everything from NASA research robots to the unveiling of the 
newest fire sculpture by the Flaming Lotus Girls.
     * A chance to talk to each other
and to some of our speakers, artists, scientists, and performers
about the big questions in or Festival of Ideas.
     * ...and much, much more!

Music

This year we are expanding our musical offerings to include TWO 
FULL STAGES, which means more performers and more variety. Check 
back frequently for updates about this year's musical line-up. 
Here's an initial list of some of our amazing musical 
performers:
Electronic music by:

     * A special twilight downtempo set by Tipper (HI)
     * John Tejada (LA/Berlin)
     * Scuba (Hotflush Recordings, UK)
     * Digitonal vs. Posthuman (UK): with live violin
     * Lusine (Ghostly Intl., Seattle): live set
     * Deru (Merck, LA): live set
     * Tycho (Ghostly, Merck): live set
     * Mr. Projectile (Merck): live set
     * ...and many more!

Live vocal and instrumental music by:

     * Telstar (Featuring: Phil Lesh, Steve Molitz, & John Molo)
     * Freezepop (Rykodisc, Boston): indie synthpop / new wave
     * Particle (LA): instrumental space-disco-dance
     * BLVD w/ Souleye (LA): hip-hop, house, & breaks
     * Zo Keating: avant garde looping cello
     * MJ Greenmountain (Hamsa Lila) vs. Yossi Fine (NY): global 
fusion and afro-tribal funk
     * Christopher Willits (12k, Ghostly Intl.): processed guitar 
soundscapes
     * Gamelan X: the intergalactic 17-member percussive melodic 
marching troupe
     * Lulacruza: Argentinan percussion, guitar, and vocals
     * ...and more!

--
------------------------------------------
terry estioko     | terry@hyperreal.org
SFRaves moderator | http://www.sfraves.org

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

On Mon, 3 Mar 2008, Terry Estioko wrote:

>
> http://www.yurisnightbayarea.com
>
> Taking place at Hangar 211, NASA Ames Reserch Center
>
> More Than a Festival...
>
> Come to Yuri's Night Bay Area to kick back, celebrate, and dance, but also be 
> ready to learn, interact, and think! You could think of Yuri's Night as a 
> fusion of a technology expo, a Maker Faire, an art exhibition, and a music 
> festival, all rolled into one.
>
> Yuri's Night Bay Area 2008 includes:
>
>    * A world-class lineup of musical artists, ranging from the ethereal 
> breakbeat sounds of Tipper to Telstar, with Phil Lesh of the Grateful Dead.
>    * A mind-expanding series of speakers, from NASA scientists to video-game 
> designers to Bay Area entrepreneurs.
>    * Live performances of all kinds, from dance and acrobatics by Capacitor 
> to aerial demonstrations featuring Yuri-Gagarin-era aerobatic aircraft.
>    * Dozens of art and science installations, including everything from NASA 
> research robots to the unveiling of the newest fire sculpture by the Flaming 
> Lotus Girls.
>    * A chance to talk to each other
> and to some of our speakers, artists, scientists, and performers
> about the big questions in or Festival of Ideas.
>    * ...and much, much more!

>> > > breakbeat sounds of Tipper to Telstar, with Phil Lesh of the Grateful
>> > Dead.
>> > >    * A mind-expanding series of speakers, from NASA scientists to
>> > video-game
>> > > designers to Bay Area entrepreneurs.
>> > >    * Live performances of all kinds, from dance and acrobatics by
>> > Capacitor
>> > > to aerial demonstrations featuring Yuri-Gagarin-era aerobatic
>> aircraft.
>> > >    * Dozens of art and science installations, including everything
>> from
>> > NASA
>> > > research robots to the unveiling of the newest fire sculpture by the
>> > Flaming
>> > > Lotus Girls.
>> > >    * A chance to talk to each other
>> > > and to some of our speakers, artists, scientists, and performers
>> > > about the big questions in or Festival of Ideas.
>> > >    * ...and much, much more!
>> > >
>> > > Music
>> > >
>> > > This year we are expanding our musical offerings to include TWO FULL
>> > STAGES,

>> > some of

>> > >    * Lusine (Ghostly Intl., Seattle): live set
>> > >    * Deru (Merck, LA): live set

>> > >    * BLVD w/ Souleye (LA): hip-hop, house, & breaks

>>>>>Yuri's Night Bay Area 2008 includes:
>>>>>
>>>>>    * A world-class lineup of musical artists, ranging from the ethereal
>>>>>breakbeat sounds of Tipper to Telstar, with Phil Lesh of the Grateful
>>>>Dead.
>>>>>    * A mind-expanding series of speakers, from NASA scientists to
>>>>video-game
>>>>>designers to Bay Area entrepreneurs.
>>>>>    * Live performances of all kinds, from dance and acrobatics by
>>>>Capacitor
>>>>>to aerial demonstrations featuring Yuri-Gagarin-era aerobatic aircraft.
>>>>>    * Dozens of art and science installations, including everything from
>>>>NASA
>>>>>research robots to the unveiling of the newest fire sculpture by the
>>>>Flaming
>>>>>Lotus Girls.
>>>>>    * A chance to talk to each other
>>>>>and to some of our speakers, artists, scientists, and performers
>>>>>about the big questions in or Festival of Ideas.
>>>>>    * ...and much, much more!
>>>>>
>>>>>Music
>>>>>
>>>>>This year we are expanding our musical offerings to include TWO FULL
>>>>STAGES,

>>>>>Electronic music by:
>>>>>
>>>>>    * A special twilight downtempo set by Tipper (HI)
>>>>>    * John Tejada (LA/Berlin)
>>>>>    * Scuba (Hotflush Recordings, UK)
>>>>>    * Digitonal vs. Posthuman (UK): with live violin
>>>>>    * Lusine (Ghostly Intl., Seattle): live set
>>>>>    * Deru (Merck, LA): live set
>>>>>    * Tycho (Ghostly, Merck): live set
>>>>>    * Mr. Projectile (Merck): live set
>>>>>    * ...and many more!
>>>>>
>>>>>Live vocal and instrumental music by:
>>>>>
>>>>>    * Telstar (Featuring: Phil Lesh, Steve Molitz, & John Molo)
>>>>>    * Freezepop (Rykodisc, Boston): indie synthpop / new wave
>>>>>    * Particle (LA): instrumental space-disco-dance
>>>>>    * BLVD w/ Souleye (LA): hip-hop, house, & breaks
>>>>>    * Zo Keating: avant garde looping cello
>>>>>    * MJ Greenmountain (Hamsa Lila) vs. Yossi Fine (NY): global fusion
>>>>and
>>>>>afro-tribal funk
>>>>>    * Christopher Willits (12k, Ghostly Intl.): processed guitar
>>>>soundscapes
>>>>>    * Gamelan X: the intergalactic 17-member percussive melodic marching
>>>>>troupe

>>>>>    * ...and more!

"The location sucks big time"

You my friend, have obviously not been to the NASA AMES facilities at
Moffett Field.  It is quite the contrary, it kicks ass, and is one of the
most awesome venues I've ever seen.  There were scares last year about
security since it is a federally ran facility, but quite honestly, we were
able to drink alcohol in the parking lot with no problem.  And once in the
party, security was near invisible.  Maybe you should check out this party
before trying to rip it.

ring fiefdoms after the fall of Rome.=20

Subject: Re: [sfraves] (nrr) QOD (Tue)



Many people refer to any period where people are allowed to do what they
don't want those people doing it as anarchy. =)

It's not his lack of history, it's his perspective that doesn't recognize
Feudalism and fiefdoms as their own form of government.  Even your basic
village geritocracy is a form of government, as is your traditional king
of the hill/alpha dog.  Warring fiefdoms are no different than warring
nations or continents.  It's a matter of scale, not the existence of
government.

No government doesn't lead to anarchy at all.  It leads to new government.

Anarchists tend to be idealists who somehow believe that if individuals
just refuse to submit to any authority things will all work out... Which
tends to overlook that most sheeple won't do any such thing.  People tend
to gravitate towards the government that most resembles the one they
recall while growing up if they had a good childhood, or the one they
grew up with the impression would have helped them.  There's little reason
in this behavioral pattern, people simply hear only as much as they need to
reinforce their political prejudice.

Now will someone invoke Godwins law and end this thread too? =)

Ray

>
>
> Many people refer to any period where people are allowed to do what they
> don't want those people doing it as anarchy. =)
>
> It's not his lack of history, it's his perspective that doesn't recognize
> Feudalism and fiefdoms as their own form of government.  Even your basic
> village geritocracy is a form of government, as is your traditional king
> of the hill/alpha dog.  Warring fiefdoms are no different than warring
> nations or continents.  It's a matter of scale, not the existence of
> government.
>
> No government doesn't lead to anarchy at all.  It leads to new government.
>
> Anarchists tend to be idealists who somehow believe that if individuals
> just refuse to submit to any authority things will all work out... Which
> tends to overlook that most sheeple won't do any such thing.  People tend
> to gravitate towards the government that most resembles the one they
> recall while growing up if they had a good childhood, or the one they
> grew up with the impression would have helped them.  There's little reason
> in this behavioral pattern, people simply hear only as much as they need 
> to
> reinforce their political prejudice.

This is a good discussion, one I want to touch on more.  I don't know =20=

that we could categorize civil disobedience as strictly something =20
that an anarchist does.  An anarchist to me simply believes there =20
should be no government and anything the public would share is sort =20
of left to individual theory, but the obvious implications would be =20
things like roads would be privately owned and maintained.

Fedualism is where the elites own everything, which is why people =20
like Alex Jones call globalism "neo-feudalism" or "neo-mercantilism", =20=

mercantilism being government's attempt to claim they own everything, =20=

and we do live in an age where they are pretty damn bold to come out =20
and say you can't smoke on your own property, or you can't have raves =20=

at the beach.  Really, says who?

I would propose that people who choose civil disobedience come from =20
all walks of life and simply decide that a particular law or rule =20
simply does not sit well with them, so they're not going to obey it.  =20=

If it's just one person, they can generally be carted off to prison =20
while everyone else sits in either fear or ignorance.  But imagine if =20=

not only Sunset decided to start doing Berkeley Marina parties every =20
Sunday, but the other past and present rave related families decided =20
"fuck the permit crap" and there were literally thousands of ravers =20
on every beach, and everywhere the police turned to confiscate one =20
sound system there were 10 more.

That's a lot of ravers, that unfortunately many have moved on, but I =20
would propose a lot of people miss those days.  The Boston Tea Party =20
happened for a reason, and we should ask ourselves, what will be the =20
2008 and beyond equivalent?

Subject: Re: [sfraves] RR: For those who STILL don't know Jack

Can you visit this place?
Can you visit this place?
Can you visit this place?

A place where music is our sanctuary, our life, where it defines our every move, where notes and measures are as important as air, water, and oxygen, a place where movement is a winding road that leads to the most beautiful rainbow of people of all colors and races, driven by one beautiful soundscape.

If you can see this place, then we can be this place, we can make this dream our reality, keep music first in your heart, keep in a sacred place, keep it free of all contempt, free of opinion.

Make it longer, stronger, better, faster.
Make it so it will never die.
Make it for a new generation.

Can you visit our place?
Can you visit THAT place?

A place where music is more important than the DJ, the promoter, the venue, the producer, your clique, your wardrobe, what your man said, what your woman said, what's hot, what's not.

Can you see this place?

Can you be this place?

>From "A New Reality" Mark Knight & MTV, Vocals E-man

Yo everybody.

First off, wanted to say thanks to everyone who made it out to [KONTROL] on
Saturday.  We had a great turnout (some of our best numbers yet according to
the Endup) and I have to say there was a particularily fat vibe for this
one!  And of course Claude VonStroke and Derek Plaslaiko both killed it!  So
thanks again to all that came out and got your groove on with us.

More importantly, I wanted to tip y'all off to a special guest who will be
playing at "Lil' Brthr" tonight @ 222 Hyde.  Yep, none other than Saturday's
hero himself, Mr. Derek Plaslaiko.  Seeing as his schedule got bumped around
a bit, he's still in town tonight, and after his sick 2 1/2 hour set at the
Endup which covered everything from house to techno to acid to minimal and
beyond, who could resist a second helping?

Hence he's been invited down as a special surprise guest tonight at this
FREE monthly gathering.  The rest of the lineup is solid as well, with
Worthy (dirtybird), Eo (Mouth2Mouth), Roman Stange (Auralism) and more
supporting.

I don't go out too often on the weeknights these days, but I'm making an
exception tonight. :)

Perhaps I'll see you there?

---->G

think they're house producers that make it such a pain to listen to 
IMHO. also i've always found house too easy to dj.. it kind of feels 
like i could stand there and i'm like 'uhh now what..?' (looking at watch)

i'm not fronting on house at all.. afterall its house that built the 
scene here in SF (albeit maybe too well...) and good tracks and house 
djs like derrick carter terry francis have rocked my world at one point 
or another. and i can't recall how many times when i was a wee young 
sprout of a raver losing my ship to simon and dj tracy.. actually one of 
my favorite dj mixes of all times is dj jazzy jeff doing doubles of 
house records! so f'n good.. i think what beat that was dave clarke 
doing doubles of hard techno `;P***** at i love techno.. um 2000?

peace, love, techno

Sean.

> >>In the beginning, there was Jack, and Jack had a groove. And from this
> groove came the groove of all grooves.And while one day viciously throwing
> down on his box, Jack boldy declared,  "Let there be HOUSE!" and house music
> was born."I am, you see, I am the creator, and this is my house!And, in my
> house there is ONLY house music.But, I am not so selfish because once you
> enter my house it then becomes OUR house and OUR house music!"And, you see,
> no one man owns house because house music is a universal language, spoken
> and understood by all. You see, house is a feeling that no one can
> understand really unless  you're deep into the vibe of house.House is an
> uncontrollable desire to jack your body.And, as I told you before, this is
> our house and our house music.And in every house, you  understand, there
> is a keeper.And, in this house, the keeper is Jack.Now some of you who
> might wonder, "Who is Jack, and what is it that Jack does?"Jack is the one
> who gives you the power to
>  jack your body! Jack is the one who gives you the power to do the
> snake.Jack is the one who gives you the   key to the wiggly worm. Jack is
> the one who learns you how to walk your body. Jack is the one that can bring
> nations and nations of all Jackers together under one house.You may be
> black, you may be white; you may be Jew or Gentile. It don't make a
> difference in OUR House.  And this is fresh.>>>

I passed that a long time ago Sean.  For the record, I was mopping my kitchen while listening and not drinking an umbrella drink on the beach unfortunately.  

Although really a really strong umbrella drink is always a good idea.  Sometimes people forget SF is a beach town...play hookey and head out to the beach with an umbrella drink today!

Peace,

Peter

PS I used the term deep to refer to the track's sound not so much what section of bins you'd find it in at Tweekin.  The mix progressed into some funky house that was bringing me back to the SF underground house sound of Panhandle Records circa 2001.  Very hot!

PPS DJ Stevian is one of my DJ heros for producing a mix that included tracks from both Primus and (yes I know they are deep house) Crazy Penis.  

Also check out the selection of downloadable mixes available at http://www.stoutcast.com/archives/

Subject: Re: [sfraves] nrr: Moses was high on drugs: Israeli researcher

This might be interesting if the person insinuating this came up with some 
examples of possible drug "culprits" that would have induced said 
hallucinations. Ayahuasca is a bad example because it's only indigineous to 
the Amazon basin (as far as I am aware).

I don know that there is "word on the street" (by way of Discovery channel) 
that says that there have been trace elements of cocaine found in some 
Egyptian Pharoah mummies....and that is clearly ONLY indigineous to South 
America - so it's POSSIBLE that Ayahuasca made it's way to that part of the 
world, but not very likely.

Maybe they were chewing on Kot or something? At any rate, I'd be much more 
impressed with this claim if the guy had backed up his claim with more info.


----- Original Message ----- 
From: "Isaac" <greylane@hotmail.com>
To: <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
Sent: Wednesday, March 05, 2008 1:29 PM
Subject: [sfraves] nrr: Moses was high on drugs: Israeli researcher



JERUSALEM (AFP)  High on Mount Sinai, Moses was on psychedelic drugs when 
he heard God deliver the Ten Commandments, an Israeli researcher claimed in 
a study published this week.
Such mind-altering substances formed an integral part of the religious rites 
of Israelites in biblical times, Benny Shanon, a professor of cognitive 
psychology at the Hebrew University of Jerusalem wrote in the Time and Mind 
journal of philosophy.

"As far Moses on Mount Sinai is concerned, it was either a supernatural 
cosmic event, which I don't believe, or a legend, which I don't believe 
either, or finally, and this is very probable, an event that joined Moses 
and the people of Israel under the effect of narcotics," Shanon told Israeli 
public radio on Tuesday.
Moses was probably also on drugs when he saw the "burning bush," suggested 
Shanon, who said he himself has dabbled with such substances.

"The Bible says people see sounds, and that is a classic phenomenon," he 
said citing the example of religious ceremonies in the Amazon in which drugs 
are used that induce people to "see music."

He mentioned his own experience when he used ayahuasca, a powerful 
psychotropic plant, during a religious ceremony in Brazil's Amazon forest in 
1991. "I experienced visions that had spiritual-religious connotations," 
Shanon said.


**************

Baby Beheaded in Saudi Supermarket

An Enraged Uncle Beheaded an 15-Month-Old Baby in Front of Mother
On Sunday morning a 25-year-old Syrian man beheaded his 15-month-old nephew 
at Al-Marhaba supermarket, Arab News reported. The man reportedly killed the 
child after an argument with his sister and brother-in-law.

This is the latest in a handful of criminal justice cases in Saudi Arabia 
that have grabbed Western attention in the last year.

In December 2008 a Saudi Arabian rape victim was charged with jail time and 
200 lashes after being found in a car with a man to whom she was not 
related - a verdict that prompted international outrage from Human Rights 
Watch and other foreign observers, including the White House and U.S. 
presidential contenders Sen. Hilary Clinton and Sen. Barack Obama. The 
woman, known anonymously in the Saudi press as "Qatif Girl" was eventually 
released from jail and later pardoned by Saudi King Abdullah.

Fawza Falih, a Saudi woman, is currently awaiting execution after being 
found guilty of witchcraft in 2005. Dozens of Saudi men were arrested last 
month for allegedly flirting with women in front of a shopping mall in 
Mecca. In January, a woman was arrested after having a Starbucks coffee with 
a male business colleague.

It's all of the above:

A NASA-backed, government approved, rave party...well 
"festival".

We were on crew last year, so we had 2 handles of liquor under 
the VJ table, we were just very careful how we dispersed it. 
There were beer vendor but the lines were long and they ran out 
early.

There were some other substances that surfaced too, but that was 
handled with the upmost discretion.

Don't know what to say about those who like to smoke doobies, 
that's hard to hide (but people still did it), and smoking 
cigarettes....they will kick you out for smoking 1 foot in the 
hangar.

And yeah, watch out for the snipers ;-)

Oh well, still fun for me, see ya there!

-terry

hen

> in

> Such mind-altering substances formed an integral part of the religious
> rites
> of Israelites in biblical times, Benny Shanon, a professor of cognitive
> psychology at the Hebrew University of Jerusalem wrote in the Time and
> Mind
> journal of philosophy.
>
> "As far Moses on Mount Sinai is concerned, it was either a supernatural
> cosmic event, which I don't believe, or a legend, which I don't believe
> either, or finally, and this is very probable, an event that joined Moses
> and the people of Israel under the effect of narcotics," Shanon told
> Israeli
> public radio on Tuesday.
> Moses was probably also on drugs when he saw the "burning bush," suggeste=
d
> Shanon, who said he himself has dabbled with such substances.
>
> "The Bible says people see sounds, and that is a classic phenomenon," he
> said citing the example of religious ceremonies in the Amazon in which
> drugs
> are used that induce people to "see music."
>
> He mentioned his own experience when he used ayahuasca, a powerful
> psychotropic plant, during a religious ceremony in Brazil's Amazon forest
> in
> 1991. "I experienced visions that had spiritual-religious connotations,"
> Shanon said.

> From: "Isaac" <greylane@hotmail.com>
> To: <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
> Sent: Wednesday, March 05, 2008 1:29 PM
> Subject: [sfraves] nrr: Moses was high on drugs: Israeli researcher
>
>
>
> JERUSALEM (AFP)  High on Mount Sinai, Moses was on psychedelic drugs when
> he heard God deliver the Ten Commandments, an Israeli researcher claimed
> in
> a study published this week.
> Such mind-altering substances formed an integral part of the religious
> rites
> of Israelites in biblical times, Benny Shanon, a professor of cognitive
> psychology at the Hebrew University of Jerusalem wrote in the Time and
> Mind
> journal of philosophy.
>
> "As far Moses on Mount Sinai is concerned, it was either a supernatural
> cosmic event, which I don't believe, or a legend, which I don't believe
> either, or finally, and this is very probable, an event that joined Moses
> and the people of Israel under the effect of narcotics," Shanon told
> Israeli
> public radio on Tuesday.
> Moses was probably also on drugs when he saw the "burning bush," suggested
> Shanon, who said he himself has dabbled with such substances.
>
> "The Bible says people see sounds, and that is a classic phenomenon," he
> said citing the example of religious ceremonies in the Amazon in which
> drugs
> are used that induce people to "see music."
>
> He mentioned his own experience when he used ayahuasca, a powerful
> psychotropic plant, during a religious ceremony in Brazil's Amazon forest
> in
> 1991. "I experienced visions that had spiritual-religious connotations,"
> Shanon said.
>
>

> nephew
> at Al-Marhaba supermarket, Arab News reported. The man reportedly killed
> the
> child after an argument with his sister and brother-in-law.
>
> This is the latest in a handful of criminal justice cases in Saudi Arabia
> that have grabbed Western attention in the last year.
>
> In December 2008 a Saudi Arabian rape victim was charged with jail time
> and
> 200 lashes after being found in a car with a man to whom she was not
> related - a verdict that prompted international outrage from Human Rights
> Watch and other foreign observers, including the White House and U.S.
> presidential contenders Sen. Hilary Clinton and Sen. Barack Obama. The
> woman, known anonymously in the Saudi press as "Qatif Girl" was eventually
> released from jail and later pardoned by Saudi King Abdullah.
>
> Fawza Falih, a Saudi woman, is currently awaiting execution after being
> found guilty of witchcraft in 2005. Dozens of Saudi men were arrested last
> month for allegedly flirting with women in front of a shopping mall in

> with
> a male business colleague.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] RR: For those who STILL don't know Jack

ok, controversy is good, it staves off boredom. ok let me clarify.. i 
like techno because its happens to have alot of drum programming that is 
based on inferred rhythms whereas house is the same rhythm most of the 
time.. which makes it predictable to me. i like house, i just find it 
too predictable for me to dj. but that's just my opinion.. i also stated 
that there are good and bad examples of every genre.

i never said that dave clarke was a great DJ but i would suggest 
listening to that i love techno mix (it seemed pretty on to me. maybe 
every other time he djs he just sucks?).. in that mix he was playing 
doubles in off time which could be confused as wrecking..? but i haven't 
heard your mix and possibly you haven't heard the mix i was speaking of. 
so we could both be right.. who knows?

you know i also find downtempo the most difficult to mix.. so many 
different tricks you have to do to just keep two records on beat. i once 
fantasized about retiring as a downtempo dj. so many layering 
opportunities and ways to be creative. so there's that, and i also have 
a strange fondness for speaker worshippers and people in extremely 
altered states.

ok so all is good in the world. no hissy fighting about my genre can 
beat up your genre.
sean
disconnect

> Ok, qst off, no EDM genre is hard to mix. Period. None of them. They are all built to mix pretty much all on the same beat/measure structues. If it ain't live drumming, it's easy. If you are having too easy of a time mixing....you are not trying hard enough to be creative with said genre. 
>
> That being aid, my current mixing obstacle is downtempo - mostly cuz of more live drum programming and just plain lack of knowledge of my tracks. That comes with time.

Subject: [sfraves] BSP~::Radio Integrated Play Schedule for March::~PSB

This Month /// March, 7th-28th 2008 /// 9pm-1am Pacific Standard Time ///

http://radio.defsf.com:1200/ <http://www.zer01.net:1200/>


DEFsf.com's Radio Integrated Marches on in March. We've been bringing 
you solid techno from all styles and sub genres of Techno without 
slacking on the talent, quality or excessive intoxication this side of 
the computer speakers each and every friday for the last 3 months. March 
looks like its going to be no exception to the rule.. with some 
satisfaction is is our pleasure to introduce this month's Radio 
Integrated line up:


*7 March//  keepin it real night. W/ DJS: Clairity, CALTROP

Keeping it real with DJs Clarity and Caltrop. Clarity is a
longtime SF techno favorite who played some records at the very first
DEF event, and we are stoked to welcome her back. A former resident of
SF electro club Tokyo Electric, Caltrop is an eclectic and creative DJ
who always keeps it groovin' with his mix of minimal, electro, house,
disco, acid, from the old school to the new school.

*14 March// "I Bleed Techno" sneak peak. W/ DJS: Disconnect, Covert

 DJ Disconnect (whoever that is) and DJ Covert will be bringing you a 
little taste of what they have in store for you at the following night's 
I Bleed Techno soiree on march 15th.. stay tuned for details.

*21 March// Techno Soul edition W/DJS: ML Tronic AKA Monty Luke, James Bass

Monty has been busting the doors down at clubs as of late and been 
basically blowing up the scene everywhere he goes. His mixing is dope, 
his tracks are on point... in short, ML Tronic is a force to be reckoned 
with! James Bass has been hibernating in Berlin for the last few months, 
but previous to that has had success in throwing his bassaholics 
anonymous parties including a one infamous underground party featuring 
DJ Bone. We look forward to hearing what fresh tracks he has in store 
for us from Bear-lin

*28 March// 420 Techno night W/ DJS: The Rhythmist, and Andy W

    Derrick the Rhythmist is one of the forerunners of the San Jose 
Techno Scene and continues to shape its ever changing sound with his 
label Dobox Recordings. His mixing is smooth and his record selection is 
fresh and is by far one of the most down to earth and passionate guys 
you'll meet in techno in the bay. Andy W has been there and back and 
held up his end of the techno scene for more than a decade. Known for 
his sets at the Cloudfactory parties, FnF parties, Harmony parties, DEF 
parties and, dare i say it, even Skills parties when they were playing 
techno, Andy has been one of the bastions of techno in the bay area and 
kept it real. We're looking forward to a Dj set by one of the people 
that continues to remain synonymous with techno in the bay area, Andy W!


Tune in at :

http://radio.defsf.com:1200/
or
http://www.zer01.net:1200/


Every Friday from 9pm - 1AM PST

Contact : radiointegrated@gmail.com

For updates on Radio Integrated, DEF, and San Francisco Bay Area techno
news and info, sign up for the DEF list at
def-announce-subscribe@defsf.com

For just the radio info:
radio-integrated-subscribe@defsf.com


///Radio Integrated :: radiointegrated@gmail.com :: 
http://radio.defsf.com:1200/  ::
Broadcasting live from Bliss Factory Studios, Alameda, CA///

Feel Free to Forward this to everyone you know. please share!!

Subject: Re: [sfraves] BSP:  Yuri's Night Bay Area 2007 - A Space and Sound Expo

Honestly, I thought they had things backwards- mainly swirly non-danceable music blasting out of the big system, inside the awesome hangar with the great visuals, and the one bastion of:

"FUCK!  It is freezing, I need to stay warm, I MUST DANCE TO LIVE!"

...was outside at the Unimog!  I generally don't get excited about the Cowboys, just too many dumb hip-hop breaks mashes, but fuck if I wasn't out by that truck half the night, grooooovin' away the icicles.

I would far rather have had a big, nice, central place to dance and freak out, and then have found various smaller (ambient, downtempo) soundsystems out on the field.

Then again, there may be a method to that madness.  Dance music is largely more divisive than non-dance oriented electronic music.  Most people can at least tolerate ambient, and it's tough not to enjoy a little downtempo, but get one Psy dickweed or one Happy Hard Handbag jerkoff up on the big system and half the party's gonna jet.  ;)

(and the other half'll jet when some techno or electro gets up there)

Who knows, anyhow I would like to officially state that I'd like to see 1500 people dancing, rather than kicking back, in that hangar this year.
-G

>
> We were on crew last year, so we had 2 handles of liquor under the  
> VJ table, we were just very careful how we dispersed it. There were  
> beer vendor but the lines were long and they ran out early.
>
> There were some other substances that surfaced too, but that was  
> handled with the upmost discretion.
>
> Don't know what to say about those who like to smoke doobies,  
> that's hard to hide (but people still did it), and smoking  
> cigarettes....they will kick you out for smoking 1 foot in the hangar.
>
> And yeah, watch out for the snipers ;-)
>
> Oh well, still fun for me, see ya there!
>
> -terry
>

through the actors, but also through music (chorus and song) and sets

Subject: [sfraves] BSP: FAKTION: Friday, 28 March: Cesare vs Disorder



2008 is rapidly shaping up to be a great year for Techno.  Just this month
the WMC is attracting much more excitement than ever before, including some
great talent.  Cesare vs Disorder is coming to the US for the first time ever.
And, what started as a quick East Coast visit (Miami and NYC) becomes a
whirlwind cross-country as he comes to the FAKTION for this exclusive West
Coast appearance!  Combined with our own multitalented DJ SAYAKA, this will
be one great party!

Friday, 28 March, 2008

RAY presents: 

F A K T I O N : because san francisco needs another techno cult
with special guests and extended sets:

Friday, 28 March 2008:
Cesare vs Disorder - Essential Reload [ Italy|UK ] 
DJ SAYAKA - BABD/Faktion [ Japan|San Francisco ]

Last Fridays @ Anu

Cesare vs Disorder:
London based, Italian born DJ, music producer, creative Cesare Marchese aka
Cesare vs Disorder (also "Queen AtOm") has been involved in the european
underground music scene for the last 10 years.  His skills and passion for
DJing has taken him around Italy, to Berlin, Poland, Finland, Switzerland,
Brazil, and of course his current home in the UK, where he continues to
also produce, having formed EssentialReload and newborn labels MEAN and
SERIALISM.

This is Cesare vs Disorder's ONLY scheduled West Coast appearance before
he returns to London, nestled in between his appearances in Miami and NYC.
Don't miss out!

DJ SAYAKA is known around the world for her consistent mastery of always
difficult downtempo, medodic techno, flawless track track selection and
natural progression.  Recently returned from her own globe-trecking gigs,
including NYC and Tokyo, it's our good fortune she's called San Francisco
home since 2004.


Anu-Bar 
43 Sixth St., San Francisco, CA
10 PM to 2 AM 21+
Cost: $5, free before 11pm

Official Site: http://www.faktionsf.com/

Coming up: Faktion: Last Fridays @ Anu 
Friday, 25 April 2008:
DJ DRAGN'FLY: DJ4NORML/DJDRAGNFLY.COM [ SAC/SF ]
DJ AMBER: Sister SF/iamthedj.com [ SF ]

Down The Rabbit Hole
A New Addition to the Beauty Process in the Via Sinistrae site.

"...Whilst Persephone is whisked away to the underworld by Hades, =
Dodgson's Alice crawl down the rabbit hole voluntarily in pursuit of the =
white rabbit. It is very clear that Dodgson, who assumed the magickally =
derived name of Lewis Carroll and in so doing accepted the Shamanic =
responsibility involved in wielding a name of power, was heavily =
influenced by the written works of 21st century Man of Knowledge, Robert =
Anton Wilson..."

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR The Vatican adds 7 new "social sins" to the list
 of deadly sins

i totally respect the original seven deadly sins because they were 
thought of and about for a very long period of time.. and didn't pop up 
out of social concerns overnight. more.. i believe they were a moral 
code that the church or the bible lacked to fight the most common faults 
of mankind. maybe if you look at these sins without the church involved 
they can be very well applied to everyone no matter what creed. i still 
believe the deadliest is pride.

especially when right wing militants talk about god, country, and 
american pride.

stay humble, i think the pride sin tells us, or risk becoming an 
asshole. and nobody likes an asshole.

i'm pretty sure these new social sins will be forgotten because they 
have essentially the same meaning as the 7 deadly sins in a new meaning.
* birth control can be curbed by the lust sin through abstenance
* drug abuse under gluttony
* pollution under sloth
* the last 3 under greed

not sure about the stemcell research thing.. but i'm sure that mankind 
messing with it's own longevity has held it back a little bit in the 
natural selection category. if you want to look at how penicillin has 
created superbacteria or how modern medicine has made it so common 
health flaws are socially acceptible. i mean look at me, i wear glasses. 
in a darwinian sense, i'm a genetic retard. i'm not about eugenics but 
if we put up with people like me for a longer period of time and my 
offspring were allowed to breed, i'd be weakening the collective gene 
pool. and lasek lazer vision correction surgeons will be making fortunes 
for generations to come. well 'thank god' for the genome project.

sean.

Ok, so...I like the mix overall, but was actually kinda sad this was way 
more dubstep than dub. Mostly cuz I think 90% of all dubstep needs an MC to 
make it dynamic.

Yes, I said that - I think 90% of dubstep needs an MC. I know most folks 
know I loathe 95% of MC's out there, cuz they tend to ruin d&b, but I think 
they actually round out the dubstep sound quite nicely if they are any good 
as an MC.

Great mixing on this mix tho. Well done.

I agree with you Deepfog to an extent. In college we debated the issue of t=
orture in 2005 when it was a hot topic because of all the events in Iraq. M=
y class was Intelligence which dealt with the KGB and CIA. The class was ve=
ry interesting. On one hand I agree with your stance on the negatives of to=
rture and the prospect that it does not actually yield any information beca=
sue the person being tortured will say anything to make the pain go away.
=20
On the other hand we have to be able to use something against enemies of th=
is country. It gets easy for us here in the U.S. to speak against inhumanit=
ies and question everything because we are relatively safe and do not deal =
with violence, intimidation, and the possibility of being killed by extremi=
sts. Well one can easily argue against violence, intimidation, and other th=
ings depending on where you live in the U.S. Especially people in the inner=
-city but for the most part you should be able to understand what I am tryi=
ng to say because I doubt the majority on this list deals with gang killing=
s and drug street turf wars on a daily basis.=20
=20
These terrorists, extremists, or whatever you might name them need to be ha=
ndled a little ruff knowing that we are not playing games. It is easy to sa=
y the U.S. started most the shit we are dealing with now in the Middle East=
 that dates back to the 40's and 50's with how we perceived and handled our=
 situation in places like Iran but this world is not fair and we all know t=
hat. I am on the fence with torture but because I am on the fence with this=
 issue I would say let's go ahead and use at least this form of torture. No=
w remember your argument makes sense to me as well like I said I am on the =
fence and inside I know it is wrong but I also know making jihad and killin=
g innocents is also wrong.
=20
Sarcastically said: As it is we now know Saddam was the right man for the j=
ob in Iraq because he had those people in check although he used and carrie=
d out the most wicked forms of torture. I read an article yesterday of how =
officials in Iraq were sent the fingers of missing security contractors in =
Iraq last week. They have been held captive for over a year.=20
=20
A great legal professor at Harvard proposed torture pass with many various =
ways in which we could use torture to a limited extent legally. I forgot th=
e idea because my instructor told us this and my class was way back in 2005=
 in my junior year of college.=20
=20
Sometimes there is no right or wrong answer to ethical questions such as to=
rture just assumption in our belief and opinion.=20

Isaac

Isaac <greylane@hotmail.com> wrote:
  
I agree with you Deepfog to an extent. In college we debated the issue of torture in 2005 when it was a hot topic because of all the events in Iraq. My class was Intelligence which dealt with the KGB and CIA. The class was very interesting. On one hand I agree with your stance on the negatives of torture and the prospect that it does not actually yield any information becasue the person being tortured will say anything to make the pain go away.

On the other hand we have to be able to use something against enemies of this country. It gets easy for us here in the U.S. to speak against inhumanities and question everything because we are relatively safe and do not deal with violence, intimidation, and the possibility of being killed by extremists. Well one can easily argue against violence, intimidation, and other things depending on where you live in the U.S. Especially people in the inner-city but for the most part you should be able to understand what I am trying to say because I doubt the majority on this list deals with gang killings and drug street turf wars on a daily basis. 

These terrorists, extremists, or whatever you might name them need to be handled a little ruff knowing that we are not playing games. It is easy to say the U.S. started most the shit we are dealing with now in the Middle East that dates back to the 40's and 50's with how we perceived and handled our situation in places like Iran but this world is not fair and we all know that. I am on the fence with torture but because I am on the fence with this issue I would say let's go ahead and use at least this form of torture. Now remember your argument makes sense to me as well like I said I am on the fence and inside I know it is wrong but I also know making jihad and killing innocents is also wrong.

Sarcastically said: As it is we now know Saddam was the right man for the job in Iraq because he had those people in check although he used and carried out the most wicked forms of torture. I read an article yesterday of how officials in Iraq were sent the fingers of missing security contractors in Iraq last week. They have been held captive for over a year. 

A great legal professor at Harvard proposed torture pass with many various ways in which we could use torture to a limited extent legally. I forgot the idea because my instructor told us this and my class was way back in 2005 in my junior year of college. 

Sometimes there is no right or wrong answer to ethical questions such as torture just assumption in our belief and opinion. 


Isaac

From: Deepfog <sfo@deepfog.com>
Date: Fri, 14 Mar 2008 21:14:30 -0700

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: torture

Isaac, it sounds like the discussions in your class didn't touch on  
the subject of government sponsored terrorism as a pretext to  
creating a false need for torture.  OK, I could be wrong, maybe you  
did, and I see from a second glance you're on the fence with this  
stuff, but a lot of people still have the ideology that the  
government won't abuse the power.  You see, it always starts with  
something that sounds reasonable.  And they mistakenly think that  
because they would never abuse the power and torture people, then  
neither would anyone else.  Not all Ted Bundy's are on death row.  A  
lot of them work for the government and are in exactly the kind of  
place where they can carry out their sick fantasies from a position  
of power, that my friend, is tyranny.

The problem is government tends to attract people that really should  
have no authority or power whatsoever.  Look at those cops that  
arrested a woman that called the police for help, then forcefully  
strip searched her, not even asking, just started ripping her clothes  
off.  Or the quadraplegic that was taken in for booking, and the  
deputy apparently didn't believe he was disabled, so she dumps him  
out of the wheelchair on the ground and tells him to get up, and is  
laughing.  All on videotape.  Look at what happened to Kevin  
Tillman.  And Khaleid Sheik Mohammed?  I would argue he was tortured  
so much and for so long that his entire case should be thrown out.   
Tasering.  I don't really want to go on, because it makes me  
completely ill to think about some of the stuff I've heard.  It's  
totally out of control.

Magna Carta and the U.S. Constitution were both literally from the  
blood of people who gave their lives because they had the guts to  
stand up to tyranny.  The reality is if it were you or I in the  
position of authority we might not even use those tactics, we might  
just "rough them up" a bit like you say.  But the problem is not  
everyone is like me and you.  There's a lot of people in military  
intelligence and even just the regular military that are like the  
Marine who killed that puppy and put it on his Myspace page, as if he  
were somehow unaccountable for his actions.  Right now the reality is  
there are total scum in the right places and they outnumber the good  
guys, who either get fired or quit in disgust.

So I don't know if that helps you understand why I think torture is  
just something that should never be validated for the good of  
everyone, including the people that carry out this "dirty work" that  
no one really wants to think about.  It's a whole lot easier to just  
not talk about it and think about this weekend's party, and I'm not  
saying it's bad to talk about that or music or whatever, I mean this  
is a rave related list, but if people don't talk about this stuff I  
think it's like driving around with bald tires or bad brakes and you  
know you don't have the money to fix it, but you keep driving it  
anyway, well what ends up happening is you pay more in the long run.

Anyway, I hope this helps out.  I've got finals so I'm making the big  
push I've got a 3,000 word essay due Wednesday (on a Star Trek  
episode, no less!) and a monologue performance on the same day, wish  
me luck!  Maybe I'll try to go out next weekend if something looks fun.

-DF

Music: house, tech house, techno
Cover: $10-20

Once again bringing you the underground vibe, DJ dreamteamer Rooz  
brings you Hotel California. Featuring Wicked house pioneers Garth and  
Jeno, and underground heroes Michael Anthony and Helicopter, you  
should expect the finest deep house and progressive beats. Throw in  
the underground location and you can rest assured that you won't be  
checking out early from this Hotel! (JV8)

sorrows, and we care about their concerns as if they were our own."  -

Subject: [sfraves] NRR: Room for rent in South Berkeley

Hey there,

If you or someone you know is looking for a place to live in the sunny  
East Bay, we will have a vacant room in our house in South Berkeley.  
The room will be available April 1st.  We can be reached at araya@tekno.us 
  or st_indigo@earthlink.net.

Please forward this to anyone you know who might be interested. Thanks!


Things to know about our household:

We own and live in the downstairs flat of a 2-unit house
Residents are: Araya (photographer), Philip (designer/builder/artist),  
Nalina (toddler/superstar), Cindy (salon owner), Sabra (preschool  
teacher), and Cemone (herbalist in training)
We all have keys to upstairs/downstairs and consider the whole thing a  
single home
Downstairs is more chill - Upstairs is a little more wild
The house is 2 short blocks from Ashby BART, 5 blocks to Berkeley Bowl  
Market and the Thai Temple
There are front & back yards with gardens/raised boxes planned, great  
if you want to do some gardening
Downstairs kitchen is huge, with a dishwasher, granite countertops
We are vegetarian, and cook two sometimes three meals a day; there is  
the option of you having shared meals with us
One cat lives here, though she may be re-located soon
Nice TV + surround sound in the living room (we like watching movies)
CDJ 800's set up in the living room
We have a washer/dryer
There is some shared storage space
There is a sewing studio & guest room upstairs
The room is 10 x 11, has ethernet, smallish closet


You:

Are male, preferably (lots of ladies in the house already, and we'd  
like to have some balance)
Do not own a lot of stuff - we already have living room furniture,  
dining room table, etc.
Want to take part in a cohesive home, and not just "have roommates"
Would actively participate in household events (i.e.: yard work days,  
bbq's, etc.)
Are mature and career-oriented, but still enjoy the occasional wild  
weekend
Can clean up after yourself (sorry, we already have a kid)
Don't have pets
Do not smoke cigarettes
Aren't a heavy drinker
Are reasonably good at communicating with housemates
Won't cook meat in our kitchen (though we do have a BBQ outside, and  
the girls upstairs cook meat occasionally)


The money part:

Rent is $640, plus utilities (PG&E $20-$60/month depending on the time  
of year and internet $5/month paid in four month installments - $20  
for four months); $640 deposit, plus $15/month for shared items like  
toilet paper, paper towels, spices, etc.

Subject: [sfraves] BSP - The new DEFsf.com is here.... like, finally!

After several years of building, scrapping, and rebuilding the site, the 
new, improved, and *actually functional* DEFSF.COM is finally up!  Check 
it out at http://www.defsf.com/main

DEF is a San Francisco based collective of independent techno DJs, 
producers, and promoters dedicated to advancing techno on the West 
Coast, by way of selflessness and partnership in the electronic dance 
music underground community. DEFsf.com is a community resource that 
features West Coast Techno news, info, articles, and interviews.  
Currently we're featuring  an in depth look at the roots of the San Jose 
techno scene, a guide to club hopping and record shopping in Berlin, and 
interviews with Greg Bird of Kontrol and Derek Scott of DoBox Recordings. 

Love techno? Want to help out with DEFsf.com?  We're looking for 
contributors in the following areas:
    *Articles and Interviews covering techno history, culture, and trends
    *Monthly DJ charts - If you're a techno DJ that wants to contribute 
to our charts for April, send a list of your top 15 tracks of the month 
to seanocean@defsf.com
    *Upcoming events - Free promotion for your upcoming techno event!  
Contact us and we'll put it on our calendar.

Special thanks goes out to DJ STML, Chel-C Faith, and Ed Colmar; without 
their hard work and dedication, none of this would be possible.

DEFsf.com is still very much a work in progress, and this is only the 
beginning.  Stay tuned.... much more to come!


Peace, love & techno always,

-sean ocean for DEF

				Well on behalf of Left Coast Techno thank you to everyone who came out =
and made our first bay area excursion a huge success!

It was everything we could have wanted and more. =20

The people, the vibe, the music, was all spot on! It was amazing to see so =
many people there for the music!

I'd
like to take this time to some of the people who went above and beyond
the call of duty to help make this party happen, Josh thanks for
helping with putting on this show man, I can't wait to see what you
have in store for your next Transcend event! Ethan from FnF, shit man
thanks for all of your support and help promoting the event we couldn't
have done it without you man, Sean and Chel-c Faith thank you for all
your help promoting and playing you guys rock! To Mek for throwing it
down with me and getting the crowd for DDR and last but not least to
all of our wondeful attendee's for providing such a wonderful
atmosphere to party it up in.

Thanks again to all who came out, expect another I Bleed Techno party in th=
e next few months.

Keep Living, loving and bleeding!

Keep checking the site for updates and links to pictures.

sean ocean <seanocean@defsf.com> wrote: After several years of building, scrapping, and rebuilding the site, the 
new, improved, and *actually functional* DEFSF.COM is finally up!  Check 
it out at http://www.defsf.com/main

DEF is a San Francisco based collective of independent techno DJs, 
producers, and promoters dedicated to advancing techno on the West 
Coast, by way of selflessness and partnership in the electronic dance 
music underground community. DEFsf.com is a community resource that 
features West Coast Techno news, info, articles, and interviews.  
Currently we're featuring  an in depth look at the roots of the San Jose 
techno scene, a guide to club hopping and record shopping in Berlin, and 
interviews with Greg Bird of Kontrol and Derek Scott of DoBox Recordings. 

Love techno? Want to help out with DEFsf.com?  We're looking for 
contributors in the following areas:
    *Articles and Interviews covering techno history, culture, and trends
    *Monthly DJ charts - If you're a techno DJ that wants to contribute 
to our charts for April, send a list of your top 15 tracks of the month 
to seanocean@defsf.com
    *Upcoming events - Free promotion for your upcoming techno event!  
Contact us and we'll put it on our calendar.

Special thanks goes out to DJ STML, Chel-C Faith, and Ed Colmar; without 
their hard work and dedication, none of this would be possible.

DEFsf.com is still very much a work in progress, and this is only the 
beginning.  Stay tuned.... much more to come!


Peace, love & techno always,

-sean ocean for DEF

west coast techno articles, news, links, music & events

++++techno news & info: def-announce-subscribe@defsf.com
++++DEF radio info: radio-integrated-subsctibe@defsf.com
