Subject: [sfraves] NRR:  Arthur C. Clarke, Premier Science Fiction Writer, Dies at 90

March 18, 2008
Arthur C. Clarke, Premier Science Fiction Writer, Dies at 90
By GERALD JONAS

Arthur C. Clarke, a writer whose seamless blend of scientific expertise =
and
poetic imagination helped usher in the space age, died early Wednesday =
in
Colombo, Sri Lanka, where he had lived since 1956. He was 90.

Rohan de Silva, an aide to Mr. Clarke, said the author died after
experiencing breathing problems, The Associated Press reported. Mr. =
Clarke
had post-polio syndrome for the last two decades and used a wheelchair.

>From his detailed forecast of telecommunications satellites in 1945, =
more
than a decade before the first orbital rocket flight, to his =
co-creation,
with the director Stanley Kubrick, of the classic science fiction film
=932001: A Space Odyssey,=94 Mr. Clarke was both prophet and promoter of =
the
idea that humanity=92s destiny lay beyond the confines of Earth.

Other early advocates of a space program argued that it would pay for =
itself
by jump-starting new technology. Mr. Clarke set his sights higher.
Paraphrasing William James, he suggested that exploring the solar system
could serve as the =93moral equivalent=94 of war, giving an outlet to =
energies
that might otherwise lead to nuclear holocaust.

Mr. Clarke=92s influence on public attitudes toward space was =
acknowledged by
American astronauts and Russian cosmonauts, by scientists like the
astronomer Carl Sagan and by movie and television producers. Gene
Roddenberry credited Mr. Clarke=92s writings with giving him courage to =
pursue
his =93Star Trek=94 project in the face of indifference, even ridicule, =
from
television executives.

In his later years, after settling in Ceylon (now Sri Lanka), Mr. Clarke
continued to bask in worldwide acclaim as both a scientific sage and the
pre-eminent science fiction writer of the 20th century. In 1998, he was
knighted by Queen Elizabeth II.

He played down his success in foretelling a globe-spanning network of
communication satellites. =93No one can predict the future,=94 he always
maintained.

But as a science fiction writer, he couldn=92t resist drawing up =
timelines for
what he called =93possible futures.=94 Far from displaying uncanny =
prescience,
these conjectures mainly demonstrated his lifelong, and often =
disappointed,
optimism about the peaceful uses of technology =97 from his calculation =
in
1945 that atomic-fueled rockets could be no more than 20 years away to =
his
conviction in 1999 that =93clean, safe power=94 from =93cold fusion=94 =
would be
commercially available in the first years of the new millennium.

Mr. Clarke was well aware of the importance of his role as science =
spokesman
to the general population: =93Most technological achievements were =
preceded by
people writing and imagining them,=94 he noted. =93I=92m sure we would =
not have
had men on the Moon,=94 he added, if it had not been for H.G. Wells and =
Jules
Verne. =93I=92m rather proud of the fact that I know several astronauts =
who
became astronauts through reading my books.=94

Arthur Charles Clarke was born on Dec. 16, 1917, in the seaside town of
Minehead, Somerset, England. His father was a farmer; his mother a post
office telegrapher. The eldest of four children, he was educated as a
scholarship student at a secondary school in the nearby town of Taunton. =
He
remembered a number of incidents in early childhood that awakened his
scientific imagination: exploratory rambles along the Somerset =
shoreline,
with its =93wonderland of rock pools;=94 a card from a pack of =
cigarettes that
his father showed him, with a picture of a dinosaur; the gift of a =
Meccano
set, a British construction toy similar to the Erector sets sold in the
United States.

He also spent time =93mapping the Moon=94 through a telescope he =
constructed
himself out of =93a cardboard tube and a couple of lenses.=94 But the =
formative
event of his childhood was his discovery, at age 13 =97 the year his =
father
died =97 of a copy of =93Astounding Stories of Super-Science,=94 then =
the leading
American science fiction magazine. He found its mix of boyish adventure =
and
far-out (sometimes bogus) science intoxicating.

While still in school, Mr. Clarke joined the newly formed British
Interplanetary Society, a small band of sci-fi enthusiasts who held the
controversial view that space travel was not only possible but could be
achieved in the not-so-distant future. In 1937, a year after he moved to
London to take a civil service job, he began writing his first science
fiction novel, a story of the far, far future that was later published =
as
=93Against the Fall of Night=94 (1953).

Mr. Clarke spent World War II as an officer in the Royal Air Force. In =
1943
he was assigned to work with a team of American scientist-engineers who =
had
developed the first radar-controlled system for landing airplanes in bad
weather. That experience led to Mr. Clarke=92s only non-science fiction =
novel,
=93Glide Path=94 (1963). More important, it led in 1945 to a technical =
paper,
published in the British journal =93Wireless World,=94 establishing the
feasibility of artificial satellites as relay stations for Earth-based
communications.

The meat of the paper was a series of diagrams and equations showing =
that
=93space stations=94 parked in a circular orbit roughly 22,240 miles =
above the
equator would exactly match the Earth=92s rotation period of 24 hours. =
In such
an orbit, a satellite would remain above the same spot on the ground,
providing a =93stationary=94 target for transmitted signals, which could =
then be
retransmitted to wide swaths of territory below. This so-called
geostationary orbit has been officially designated the Clarke Orbit by =
the
International Astronomical Union.

Decades later, Mr. Clarke called his =93Wireless World=94 paper =93the =
most
important thing I ever wrote.=94 In a wry piece entitled, =93A Short =
Pre-History
of Comsats, Or: How I Lost a Billion Dollars in My Spare Time,=94 he =
claimed
that a lawyer had dissuaded him from applying for a patent. The lawyer, =
he
said, thought the notion of relaying signals from space was too =
far-fetched
to be taken seriously.

But Mr. Clarke also acknowledged that nothing in his paper =97 from the =
notion
of artificial satellites to the mathematics of the geostationary orbit =
=97 was
new. His chief contribution was to clarify and publicize an idea whose =
time
had almost come =97 a feat of consciousness-raising that he would =
continue to
excel at throughout his career.

The year 1945 also saw the launch of Mr. Clarke=92s career as a fiction
writer. He sold a short story called =93Rescue Party=94 to the same =
magazine =97
now re-titled Astounding Science Fiction =97 that had captured his =
imagination
15 years earlier.

For the next two years, Mr. Clarke attended Kings College, London, on =
the
British equivalent of a G.I. Bill scholarship, graduating in 1948 with
first-class honors in physics and mathematics. But he continued to write =
and
sell stories, and after a stint as assistant editor at the scientific
journal Physics Abstracts, he decided he could support himself as a
freelance writer. Success came quickly. His primer on space flight, =
=93The
Exploration of Space,=94 was a Book-of-the-Month Club selection in 1951

Over the next two decades, he wrote a series of nonfiction bestsellers =
as
well as his best-known novels, including =93Childhood=92s End=94 (1953) =
and =932001:
A Space Odyssey=94 (1968). For a scientifically trained writer whose =
optimism
about technology seemed boundless, Mr. Clarke delighted in confronting =
his
characters with obstacles they could not overcome without help from =
forces
beyond their comprehension.

In =93Childhood=92s End,=94 a race of aliens who happen to look like =
devils
imposes peace on an Earth torn by cold war tensions. But the aliens=92 =
real
mission is to prepare humanity for the next stage of evolution. In an =
ending
that is both heartbreakingly poignant and literally earth-shattering, =
Mr.
Clarke suggests that mankind can escape its suicidal tendencies only by
ceasing to be human.

=93There was nothing left of Earth,=94 he wrote. =93It had nourished =
them, through
the fierce moments of their inconceivable metamorphosis, as the food =
stored
in a grain of wheat feeds the infant plant while it climbs toward the =
Sun.=94

The cold war also forms the backdrop for =932001.=94 Its genesis was a =
short
story called =93The Sentinel,=94 first published in a science fiction =
magazine
in 1951. It tells of an alien artifact found on the Moon, a little
crystalline pyramid that explorers from Earth destroy while trying to =
open.
One explorer realizes that the artifact was a kind of fail-safe beacon; =
in
silencing it, human beings have signaled their existence to its far-off
creators.

In the spring of 1964, Stanley Kubrick, fresh from his triumph with =
=93Dr.
Strangelove or: How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Bomb,=94 met =
Mr.
Clarke in New York, and the two agreed to make the =93proverbial really =
good
science fiction movie=94 based on =93The Sentinel.=94 This led to a =
four-year
collaboration; Mr. Clarke wrote the novel while Mr. Kubrick produced and
directed the film; they are jointly credited with the screenplay.

Reviewers at the time were puzzled by the film, especially the final =
scene
in which an astronaut who has been transformed by aliens returns to =
orbit
the Earth as a =93Star-Child.=94 In the book he demonstrates his =
new-found
powers by harmlessly detonating from space the entire arsenal of Soviet =
and
American nuclear weapons. Like much of the plot, this denouement is not
clear in the film, from which Mr. Kubrick cut most of the expository
material.

As a fiction writer, Mr. Clarke was often criticized for failing to =
create
fully realized characters. HAL, the mutinous computer in =932001,=94 is =
probably
his most =93human=94 creation: a self-satisfied know-it-all with a =
touching but
misguided faith in its own infallibility.

If Mr. Clarke=92s heroes are less than memorable, it is also true that =
there
are no out-and-out villains in his work; his characters are generally =
too
busy struggling to make sense of an implacable universe to engage in =
petty
schemes of dominance or revenge.

Mr. Clarke=92s own relationship with machines was somewhat ambivalent.
Although he held a driver=92s license as a young man, he never drove a =
car.
Yet he stayed in touch with the rest of the world from his home in Sri =
Lanka
through an ever-expanding collection of up-to-date computers and
communications accessories. And until his health declined, he was an =
expert
scuba diver in the waters around Sri Lanka.

He first became interested in diving in the early 1950s, when he =
realized
that he could find underwater =93something very close to =
weightlessness=94 of
outer space. He settled permanently in Colombo, the capital of what was =
then
Ceylon, in 1956. With a partner, he established a guided diving service =
for
tourists and wrote vividly about his diving experiences in a number of
books, beginning with =93The Coast of Coral=94 (1956).

All told, he wrote or collaborated on close to 100 books, some of which,
like =93Childhood=92s End,=94 have been in print continuously. His works =
have been
translated into some 40 languages, and worldwide sales have been =
estimated
at more than $25 million.

In 1962 he suffered a severe attack of poliomyelitis. His apparently
complete recovery was marked by a return to top form at his favorite =
sport,
table tennis. But in 1984 he developed post-polio syndrome, a =
progressive
condition characterized by muscle weakness and extreme fatigue. He spent =
the
last years of his life in a wheelchair.

Among his legacies are Clarke=92s Three Laws, provocative observations =
on
science, science fiction and society that were published in his =
=93Profiles of
the Future=94 (1962):

=B6=93When a distinguished but elderly scientist states that something =
is
possible, he is almost certainly right. When he states that something is
impossible, he is very probably wrong.=94

=B6=93The only way of discovering the limits of the possible is to =
venture a
little way past them into the impossible.=94

=B6=93Any sufficiently advanced technology is indistinguishable from =
magic.=94

Along with Verne and Wells, Mr. Clarke said his greatest influences as a
writer were Lord Dunsany, a British fantasist noted for his lyrical, if
sometimes overblown, prose; Otto Stapledon, a British philosopher who =
wrote
vast speculative narratives that projected human evolution to the =
furthest
reaches of space and time; and Herman Melville=92s =93Moby-Dick.=94

While sharing his passions for space and the sea with a worldwide
readership, Mr. Clarke kept his emotional life private. He was briefly
married in 1953 to an American diving enthusiast named Marilyn Mayfield;
they separated after a few months and were divorced in 1964.

One of his closest relationships was with Leslie Ekanayake, a fellow =
diver
in Sri Lanka, who died in a motorcycle accident in 1977. Mr. Clarke =
shared
his home in Colombo with Leslie=92s brother, Hector, his partner in the =
diving
business, Hector=92s wife Valerie; and their three daughters.

Mr. Clarke=92s standard answer when journalists asked him outright if he =
was
gay was, =93No, merely mildly cheerful.=94

Mr. Clarke reveled in his fame. One whole room in his house =97 which he
referred to as the Ego Chamber =97 was filled with photos and other
memorabilia of his career, including pictures of him with Yuri Gagarin, =
the
first man in space, and Neil Armstrong, the first man to walk on the =
moon.

Mr. Clarke=92s reputation as a prophet of the space age rests on more =
than a
few accurate predictions. His visions helped bring about the future he
longed to see. His contributions to the space program were lauded by =
Charles
Kohlhase, who planned NASA=92s Cassini mission to Saturn: =93When you =
dream what
is possible, and add a knowledge of physics, you make it happen.=94

See also, http://www.amazon.com/Kindly-Bent-Ease-Part-One/dp/0913546402

And this lecture reminds me of a track: 
http://www.audiojelly.com/index.cfm?action=track.cfm?id=52427&type=tracks

Read below while enjoying a little bit o' psy trance.

The Natural Freedom of the Mind

Since the One Mind -- pure from the beginningless beginning
and with no need to grasp things other than itself --
has nothing to do with an intermediary or with a fixed plan ,
the individual mind might as well
be happy .

Since awareness has no objective relationship of any kind,
no specific direction or focus ,
the individual might as well
love everyone .

Since vision and commitment to vision
have nothing to do with complacency or fear,
the individual might as well
be joyous .

Since action and goals have nothing to do with success or failure,
hope and anxiety ,
and it doesn't matter whether they are won or lost ,
the individual might as well
feel content .

Since everything is an illusion --
with some more perfect than others --
with no relationship to good or bad ,
being or not-being ,
one might as well
laugh from beginning to end .

 Longchenpa

Peace,

Peter

From: Phillip Mispagel <phillip@viberation.com>
To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
Sent: Wednesday, March 19, 2008 8:18:16 PM
Subject: [sfraves] BSP: Moksha Tribe presents PHOENIX 3/29/2008

PRESALES GOING FAST GET YOUR TICKETS QUICK
        Saturday March 29th, 2008
10PM to 6AM
  In celebration of the rebirth of MOKSHA TRIBE, we bring you... 
      PHOENIX
      Purchase Pre-sales tickets here: phoenix.mokshatribe.net

      A universal symbol of the sun, mystical rebirth, resurrection and immortality, this legendary red "fire bird" was believed to die in its self-made flames periodically then rise again out of its own ashes. Linked to the worship of the fiery sun and sun gods such as  Mexico 's Quetzalcoatl, it was named "a god of Phoenicia " by the Phoenician. To alchemists, it symbolized the destruction and creation of new forms of matter along the way to the ultimate transformation: physical and spiritual

  Two full rooms of music with new and past Moksha Tribe decorations. Come dressed in the theme of Fire and Flight! 
                        Fire Room
- Forest Green (ForestGreen.org Cute Fang Recordings)
- Dragn'fly (DJDragnFly.com, DJ4NORML)
- AndyW vs Chris Jackson (Resource Records Tagteam)
- Andy Kaotik (Audio Dream Control,  Boston , MA )
- ShezTek (Moksha Tribe)
- NomadicDJ (Moksha Tribe)
                    Flight Room
- Bam (Evil Breaks)
- Brian Behlendorf (Cloudfactory, FNF, Hyperreal)
- DV8 (Moksha Tribe)
- Jose Padilla (Moksha Tribe)
- Marcine (Moksha Tribe)
            Visuals by Viberation
Sound by SWAT
Lighting by Radiant Atmospheres
Hookah service provided by Fauxdive
  Convenient Bay Area underground location 
  18+
      This event is dedicated to Apollo & Joey for the vision, the dream, and
  the love they created. 
        As always, you will be treated with love and respect!

  ALL PROFITS FROM THIS EVENT WILL BE DONATED TO LARKIN STREET YOUTH SERVICES
  www.larkinstreetyouth.org
      Limited presale tickets are now available for $15.00

So, it's no surprise really to folks around here that I have been strugglin=
g on and off with financial bullshit. After shelling out almost a grand to =
the IRS this year, they decided to nail me with another $600 penalty for so=
me mini audit they did on my 2006 returns, and have begun snatching money o=
ut of my checks. My rent increased from less than $600 per month to $750 pe=
r month in January, and my commute costs went up from less than $50 a month=
 to over $200 a month. Essentially, I have far more money going out to debt=
 then I am making.=20

I have tried to sell off my records and whatnot to try and make up the loss=
, but I haven't even really scratched the surface (but thank you to those w=
ho have purchased from me, hopefully the vinyl has been worth it).=20

I am now about $400 overdrawn in my bank after the gub'ment took a nice chu=
nk from me and my landlord cashed a check for utilities that I asked him to=
 hold up on until I could recoup some lost cash. I am essentially screwed f=
or rent money on the 31st/1st as my check will be swallowed up paying back =
the bank.=20

This is the worst possible scenario I could face right now. I'd borrow from=
 my parents, but to be honest, they are struggling on their paltry retireme=
nt incomes to the point where my mother had to get a job to make ends meet.=
 I have tried to get a loan through my work, but they don't want to do that=
, because they feel if they help me, the floodgates will open for other emp=
loyees to seek assistance.=20

Basically, I am up the proverbial shit creek sans paddle. I am not expectin=
g a miracle to happen by any means - but if anyone has any suggestions, or =
can offer help, I am by no means beyond accepting at this point.=20

On top of all this, I caught a wicked fever/flu last night, and am missing =
a day of work that I can't afford to miss at all.=20

I am not the type of person to just accept charity without trying to pay ba=
ck...so if anyone knows of people who may need help around the house (like =
painting or cleaning or something), or maybe need some one off job of some =
kind, or anything really...please let me know! My weekends are my only real=
ly free days as my job has me commuting for 4 hours per day (2 hours there,=
 2 hours back), but I'd be willing to do just about anything at this point =
to try and get myself out of this hole.=20

How about it SFR...help a fellow raver?

~ Marco

Subject: [sfraves] (nrr) QOD (Thu)

http://www.foreignaffairs.org/20070501faessay86308/benn-steil/the-end-of-national-currency.html

--

National currencies and global markets simply do not mix; together
they make a deadly brew of currency crises and geopolitical tension
and create ready pretexts for damaging protectionism. In order to
globalize safely, countries should abandon monetary nationalism and
abolish unwanted currencies, the source of much of today's instability.

- Benn Steil, Council on Foreign Relations

On Thu, Mar 20, 2008 at 11:08 AM, <electrofunk138@hotmail.com> wrote:

>
> So, it's no surprise really to folks around here that I have been
> struggling on and off with financial bullshit. After shelling out almost a
> grand to the IRS this year, they decided to nail me with another $600
> penalty for some mini audit they did on my 2006 returns, and have begun
> snatching money out of my checks. My rent increased from less than $600 per
> month to $750 per month in January, and my commute costs went up from less
> than $50 a month to over $200 a month. Essentially, I have far more money
> going out to debt then I am making.
>
> I have tried to sell off my records and whatnot to try and make up the
> loss, but I haven't even really scratched the surface (but thank you to
> those who have purchased from me, hopefully the vinyl has been worth it).
>
> I am now about $400 overdrawn in my bank after the gub'ment took a nice
> chunk from me and my landlord cashed a check for utilities that I asked him
> to hold up on until I could recoup some lost cash. I am essentially screwed
> for rent money on the 31st/1st as my check will be swallowed up paying back
> the bank.
>
> This is the worst possible scenario I could face right now. I'd borrow
> from my parents, but to be honest, they are struggling on their paltry
> retirement incomes to the point where my mother had to get a job to make
> ends meet. I have tried to get a loan through my work, but they don't want
> to do that, because they feel if they help me, the floodgates will open for
> other employees to seek assistance.
>
> Basically, I am up the proverbial shit creek sans paddle. I am not
> expecting a miracle to happen by any means - but if anyone has any
> suggestions, or can offer help, I am by no means beyond accepting at this
> point.
>
> On top of all this, I caught a wicked fever/flu last night, and am missing
> a day of work that I can't afford to miss at all.
>
> I am not the type of person to just accept charity without trying to pay
> back...so if anyone knows of people who may need help around the house (like
> painting or cleaning or something), or maybe need some one off job of some
> kind, or anything really...please let me know! My weekends are my only
> really free days as my job has me commuting for 4 hours per day (2 hours
> there, 2 hours back), but I'd be willing to do just about anything at this
> point to try and get myself out of this hole.
>
> How about it SFR...help a fellow raver?

license suspended within the last few years, you may be able to work a shift
or two, but they'll find out and pull you off unfortunately.  Can't drive
Maserati's and Bentley's unless your shit is clean.

suspension? i'm facing this myself especially since i cannot afford to

really hard with a sandpaper condom when you're poor. i would suggest 
trawling craigslist for gigs. there's lots of weird stuff in there that

looking to cheat somebody out of an honest days work.

and all you people in your cubicles reading this now.. thank your lucky 
monitor you have a decent living wage. whatever bs your boss puts you 
through its not half as bad as being late on all your bills and rent.

respects
sean.

hey man, sorry to hear about your hard times. i don't know if this is what you're after, but i work part time in a restaurant on the wharf (in addition to my full-time office job) and i could probably get you a shift or two hosting on the weekends. i think it pays $10/hour, and you basically just stand outside, say hello to tourists, and lead people to their tables. let me know if you're interested and i'll talk to the owner for you. good luck <3

electrofunk138@hotmail.com wrote: 
So, it's no surprise really to folks around here that I have been struggling on and off with financial bullshit. After shelling out almost a grand to the IRS this year, they decided to nail me with another $600 penalty for some mini audit they did on my 2006 returns, and have begun snatching money out of my checks. My rent increased from less than $600 per month to $750 per month in January, and my commute costs went up from less than $50 a month to over $200 a month. Essentially, I have far more money going out to debt then I am making. 

I have tried to sell off my records and whatnot to try and make up the loss, but I haven't even really scratched the surface (but thank you to those who have purchased from me, hopefully the vinyl has been worth it). 

I am now about $400 overdrawn in my bank after the gub'ment took a nice chunk from me and my landlord cashed a check for utilities that I asked him to hold up on until I could recoup some lost cash. I am essentially screwed for rent money on the 31st/1st as my check will be swallowed up paying back the bank. 

This is the worst possible scenario I could face right now. I'd borrow from my parents, but to be honest, they are struggling on their paltry retirement incomes to the point where my mother had to get a job to make ends meet. I have tried to get a loan through my work, but they don't want to do that, because they feel if they help me, the floodgates will open for other employees to seek assistance. 

Basically, I am up the proverbial shit creek sans paddle. I am not expecting a miracle to happen by any means - but if anyone has any suggestions, or can offer help, I am by no means beyond accepting at this point. 

On top of all this, I caught a wicked fever/flu last night, and am missing a day of work that I can't afford to miss at all. 

I am not the type of person to just accept charity without trying to pay back...so if anyone knows of people who may need help around the house (like painting or cleaning or something), or maybe need some one off job of some kind, or anything really...please let me know! My weekends are my only really free days as my job has me commuting for 4 hours per day (2 hours there, 2 hours back), but I'd be willing to do just about anything at this point to try and get myself out of this hole. 

How about it SFR...help a fellow raver?

~ Marco

Bunny Jam is tonight folks!  And as I mentioned earlier, I'm going to be 
getting full on weird with my set from Midnight to 1:23a in the downstairs 
dancefloor area.  Knowledge of Bunny Jam has apparently spread fairly wide, so 
I'd suggest getting there early to make sure that you get in as well as 
maximizing the fun. ;)

Full details are here: http://bunnyjam.com/ (be sure to check out past pictures 
for inspiration.)

And for a little sampling of the musical weirdness, be sure to check out some 
of Neon Bunny's sets here: http://www.neonbunny.com/  You definitely don't want 
to sleep on this one.

Hope to see you on the dancefloor!

Namaste.

Hey all,

I've been on the hunt for some cheap/used rims and tires for my '94 Acura
Integra.  I've been keeping an eye out on CL, but then it hit me, maybe i
should check here as well.  i'd have more faith in my friends here on SFR
than some random CL posting.

I'm currently riding on some basic rims (sans hubcaps) with some abused
Falken tires.  I had to use some "Fix it Flat" to get me up and running and
it has really screwed up the balance on my tires.  Rather than just getting
new tires i thought i'd try to keep an eye out for some decent rims and
tires.  I was hoping to come across just some basic stock alloy rims with
tires in good condition, but anything more than that is worth checking out
as well.  14's, 15's, 16's or 17's (as long as it has a 4x100mm lug pattern
and is in good condition) it doesnt really matter.  So if you've swapped out
your rims and tires for new fancy ones and still have the old ones sitting
in a garage somewhere or know someone else who does and want to get rid of
them for cheap (or trade, i dont have too much stuff up to offer in trade
but you never know) let me know.

As always thanks for your help fellow SFR friends.

-- 
Chester Copperpot

"Dead people are the new Potatos!"
"Meth Monsters are my Anti-Drug"

Formless (Flytrap / Day of Hugs / Bete Noire - UK)

Dan Jones is a London based DJ and producer with a long-standing passion =
for underground house music. Djing and producing under the name =
Formless, he has been rocking clubs around London with a blend of =
forward thinking tech house and dirty electro beats.=20
In the last 12 months he has been creating a buzz with his unique, =
energetic, upfront sound at respected London venues like The Cross, =
Turnmills, Pacha, The Key and The Island. His brisk ascent through the =
DJ ranks came on the back of a number of DJ mix competition wins and =
playing a live set on MoS Radio. This gave the exposure needed to push =
his sound onto bigger dancefloors. Having consolidated his position in =
London, Formless is now taking his music to the international club =
scene.=20

With more dates in San Francisco, Sydney, Brisbane and the Ukraine on =
the horizon, time in the studio working on a new solo EP and a number of =
remixes and collaborations, the future looks bright for one of djing's =
freshest talents. On top of DJ and production commitments Dan has just =
launched his own night Flytrap, already hosting parties at The Cross, =
The Island & Pacha London. He still finds time every summer to =
co-ordinate the music for the Norgstock Festival (nr. Stonehenge) and =
run his own Day of Hugs bi-annual Manor House Party (nr. Bournemouth).=20

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Hi

It seems that most non-underground events that I go to are at Mighty.  
I don't prefer the venue, it's just that all the events that I like  
happen to be there. My favorite venue in SF is probably Mezzanine.  
There are breaks events all the time. Look for flyers in clubs,  
record stores, and bars.

Sadly, the sfraves list is not a real reflection of what goes on in  
the sf bay area.  The music and dance scene in SF is quite positive,  
varied and lively. You'll eventually find what you're looking for. :)

Welcome!
-andy

In light of some recent commentary, I thought it might be cool to have a 1015 discussion for a minute. For better AND worse, I have had some F'n good times there. . . 

I remember when they used to throw Come-Unity at 1015, there was Nikita on Friday night, Release on Sat., then Spundae on Sundays. . . The big name DJ's rocked the club to a packed crowd, and the debauchery in the basement was taken to a new level.

Yeah, there was the "Nazi Security" phase (they've been pretty cool since remodeling), but I still have a good time when I go there, esp. on a busy night. The indoor smoking area is a great touch, because you can still hear the music and have a smoke without freezing your ass off. (BTW, I haven't have a cigarette since Feb. 8th, but the security there has been pretty "lenient" with us, if you catch me drift.)

I guess my favorite parties I've seen there lately are the Get Freaky events. My experience with that crowd has been really positive, and the acid/funky/industrial break/burner sound really thumps the sound in that main room. 

I guess what I'm trying to say here that 1015 still has a strong "vibe" factor at select events. Just gotta be weary of what night you're going now.

My .02, rant away.

peace

CKG





--0-742826063-1206387159=:92434--

Well, they are moving away from the EDM crowd to focus more on live music 
anyway - I think 1015's era of electronic tunes is on it's way out.

I for one couldn't care less. I love the upstairs and basement, but have 
always thought the front room and main room have (by and large) sucked. 
Often times the sound in the main area was muddy and unclear - which in a 
big room is god awful.

The last really good event I went to there was Cut Chemist last year. WODNB 
last year was HORRIBLE. I mean, realllllllllllllllllllllly bad. The sound 
sucked, and only two DJ's (Danny The Wildchild & Method 1) were worth a 
fuck. The MC's were positively attrocious (albeit kinda hot - they were 
female MC's).

I dunno - I just never saw the appeal. I hate to say it, but I'd rather go 
to Ruby Skye.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] nrr: are we heading in for more than a recession?

First off, some sites to check out:

http://www.theinternationalforecaster.com

http://www.midasresources.com

http://www.usgoldcoins.com/

I didn't catch everything Andy Gause said the other night on the Jeff  
Rense show but he did explain quite clearly why gold went to over  
$1,000 last week and now it's dropped but it's definitely expected to  
go up again.  I believe the only reason it hasn't shot up even more  
is the central banks are dumping gold into the market.

Now one thing about this is Alan Greenspan was one of the people  
responsible for this mess we're in now, as well as all the lending  
institutions that gave all those subprime and ALT-A loans that now  
have people in new tent cities springing up in Los Angeles and other  
areas of the country.  Ben Bernanke is making it worse and when he  
talks, he talks like we're two years old.

They're doing this on purpose and everyone knows this, because  
depending on how bad it gets, there's two models I've heard as  
possibilities, one is like the 1970's stagflation era, the other is  
the 1930's depression style.  Keep in mind that both of them carry  
the danger of inflation, but it could get so bad that your dollar  
will no longer be able to buy food.  This happened in the 1930's in  
the Weimar Republic and it also happened in Argentina a few years  
back.  And if that kind of stuff happens it doesn't take much for  
normal upstanding people to start acting like animals, coming to your  
door looking for your food.  Will it get that bad?  I hope not.

Last thing I'm going to talk about right now, and I haven't vetted  
some of this information with books and periodicals yet, so do your  
own research, is if you decide to buy gold, remember the government  
has claimed their right to confiscate it under executive order, so  
basically circumventing the entire system, unless it is pre-1933  
coins or collectibles.  They did it in 1933, made everyone turn in  
their gold for I believe it was $20 an ounce, then when they got it  
all they raised the price to $35 an ounce, but you couldn't get this  
price if you were an American.  If they confiscate gold now, it will  
be at $42 an ounce.  So be careful and get it from trusted sources,  
I've posted a few links of places you could call there's also  
Gainesville Coins on eBay that's pretty prompt.

Get some gold and silver, get some storable food or grow a garden,  
diversify.  Next 2-3 years is when it could all crash from every  
source I've heard.  Or it could even be tomorrow.

worth the shows they put on...  

XM is much cheaper, but has less electronic/dance stations.

We'll see who pops up next to be the competition... Maybe it will get
cheaper ;)

My luck with the Garmin traffic antenna has been hit & miss. Not sure if that's the same as what you're describing below, however I believe they all use the same service for traffic "updates". . . Works OK for traffic warnings in the bay, however I usually ignore them unless there is a "red" warning, in which I'll detour.

For the snow, it's so far proved worthless ("warning: chains required ahead," as opposed to the radio will fill you in on the 5 hours that you'll be stuck on 80 if you don't turn the F around RIGHT NOW!!!)

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Hi

This is a list of sites that I like to check out (since i do all that 
promo stuff);
1. NiteVibe
2.SFStation
3.SunsetPromotions
4.Eventvibe
For events that are not really on the radar;
1. go to the Haight and pick up every flyer u see that may look 
intresting to you for up incoming events
2. Find the local artist that you like in these flyers and subscribe to 
there myspace or such so, you could get there bulletins for up incoming 
events.
3. when you get out after doing the above, you find more information by 
word of mouth, by a flyer handed to you, put on your car, or just 
laying around a venue. If by any chance you run into the person that is 
handing out flyers or is putting them on your car, you could ask him 
"what else is going on tonight?" they will most likely be able to 
assist you in that.

PHOENIX
Purchase Pre-sales tickets here: phoenix.mokshatribe.net

A universal symbol of the sun, mystical rebirth, resurrection and immortality, 
this legendary red "fire bird" was believed to die in its self-made flames 
periodically then rise again out of its own ashes. Linked to the worship of 
the fiery sun and sun gods such as Mexico's Quetzalcoatl, it was named "a god 
of Phoenicia" by the Phoenician. To alchemists, it symbolized the destruction 
and creation of new forms of matter along the way to the ultimate 
transformation: physical and spiritual

Two full rooms of music with new and past Moksha Tribe decorations. Come 
dressed in the theme of Fire and Flight!

On Mon, Mar 24, 2008 at 2:12 PM, Deepfog <sfo@deepfog.com> wrote:

> First off, some sites to check out:
>
> http://www.theinternationalforecaster.com
>
> http://www.midasresources.com
>
> http://www.usgoldcoins.com/
>
> I didn't catch everything Andy Gause said the other night on the Jeff
> Rense show but he did explain quite clearly why gold went to over
> $1,000 last week and now it's dropped but it's definitely expected to
> go up again.  I believe the only reason it hasn't shot up even more
> is the central banks are dumping gold into the market.
>
> Now one thing about this is Alan Greenspan was one of the people
> responsible for this mess we're in now, as well as all the lending
> institutions that gave all those subprime and ALT-A loans that now
> have people in new tent cities springing up in Los Angeles and other
> areas of the country.  Ben Bernanke is making it worse and when he
> talks, he talks like we're two years old.
>
> They're doing this on purpose and everyone knows this, because
> depending on how bad it gets, there's two models I've heard as
> possibilities, one is like the 1970's stagflation era, the other is
> the 1930's depression style.  Keep in mind that both of them carry
> the danger of inflation, but it could get so bad that your dollar
> will no longer be able to buy food.  This happened in the 1930's in
> the Weimar Republic and it also happened in Argentina a few years
> back.  And if that kind of stuff happens it doesn't take much for
> normal upstanding people to start acting like animals, coming to your
> door looking for your food.  Will it get that bad?  I hope not.
>
> Last thing I'm going to talk about right now, and I haven't vetted
> some of this information with books and periodicals yet, so do your
> own research, is if you decide to buy gold, remember the government
> has claimed their right to confiscate it under executive order, so
> basically circumventing the entire system, unless it is pre-1933
> coins or collectibles.  They did it in 1933, made everyone turn in
> their gold for I believe it was $20 an ounce, then when they got it
> all they raised the price to $35 an ounce, but you couldn't get this
> price if you were an American.  If they confiscate gold now, it will
> be at $42 an ounce.  So be careful and get it from trusted sources,
> I've posted a few links of places you could call there's also
> Gainesville Coins on eBay that's pretty prompt.
>
> Get some gold and silver, get some storable food or grow a garden,
> diversify.  Next 2-3 years is when it could all crash from every
> source I've heard.  Or it could even be tomorrow.
>
>

> > If you haven't been seeing this coming since about 2002, you
> > haven't been
> > paying attention.
> >
> > Yes, it's going to get bad. REALLY fucking bad.

> > will no longer be able to buy food.  This happened in the 1930's in

> > back.  And if that kind of stuff happens it doesn't take much for
> > normal upstanding people to start acting like animals, coming to your
> > door looking for your food.  Will it get that bad?  I hope not.

> > has claimed their right to confiscate it under executive order, so
> > basically circumventing the entire system, unless it is pre-1933
> > coins or collectibles.  They did it in 1933, made everyone turn in
> > their gold for I believe it was $20 an ounce, then when they got it
> > all they raised the price to $35 an ounce, but you couldn't get this
> > price if you were an American.  If they confiscate gold now, it will
> > be at $42 an ounce.  So be careful and get it from trusted sources,
> > I've posted a few links of places you could call there's also
> > Gainesville Coins on eBay that's pretty prompt.
> >
> > Get some gold and silver, get some storable food or grow a garden,
> > diversify.  Next 2-3 years is when it could all crash from every
> > source I've heard.  Or it could even be tomorrow.

> > will no longer be able to buy food.  This happened in the 1930's in
> > the Weimar Republic and it also happened in Argentina a few years
> > back.  And if that kind of stuff happens it doesn't take much for
> > normal upstanding people to start acting like animals, coming to your
> > door looking for your food.  Will it get that bad?  I hope not.
> >
> > Last thing I'm going to talk about right now, and I haven't vetted
> > some of this information with books and periodicals yet, so do your
> > own research, is if you decide to buy gold, remember the government
> > has claimed their right to confiscate it under executive order, so
> > basically circumventing the entire system, unless it is pre-1933
> > coins or collectibles.  They did it in 1933, made everyone turn in
> > their gold for I believe it was $20 an ounce, then when they got it
> > all they raised the price to $35 an ounce, but you couldn't get this
> > price if you were an American.  If they confiscate gold now, it will
> > be at $42 an ounce.  So be careful and get it from trusted sources,
> > I've posted a few links of places you could call there's also
> > Gainesville Coins on eBay that's pretty prompt.
> >
> > Get some gold and silver, get some storable food or grow a garden,
> > diversify.  Next 2-3 years is when it could all crash from every
> > source I've heard.  Or it could even be tomorrow.
> >
> >

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: Police search homes for guns in DC - ILLEGAL/UNETHICAL?

this is a good time to remind you all -  DO NOT EVER let the po-po in  
unless they have a warrant, or unless you were the one who called  
them!  this also goes for event venues.

if they show up at your event, lock the door behind you (have a secret  
knock set up ahead of time), go outside and chat. make sure you have  
I.D. on you. if there was a noise complaint made, offer to turn the  
music down.

i've done this twice, and it has worked the same way both times. the  
cops took down my info, gave me a warning, and said if they got  
another complaint and came back, they were giving me a citation.

it's important that 1) there's no olfactory or visual evidence of  
something fishy going on inside, 2) you're sober when you talk with  
them, and 3) there are no minors in view.

no warrant = no entry.  don't be a pushover and let them in when they  
say "mind if we have a look around?"  that's how you get busted!

s something or has something to add by experience or hearsay. Letting a pol=
ice officer search your home or car with your consent and no warrant is leg=
al but you are asking for troulbe if you agree and have something illegal i=
n your home or car.=20
=20
In college we use to debate this topic in class when I was writing my senio=
r thesis as an undergrad. We all know that if an officer does not have a wa=
rrant and has to ask then they do not have enough probable cause to conduct=
 the search. Although here is the catch that mostly applies to people in au=
tomobiles.=20
=20
Police pressure people and use many different tactics to persuade people to=
 conduct a search by asking them making it legal. I read a great case and I=
 recommend anyone with enough time on there hands to read it because it set=
s the precedent for illegal searches with the Supreme Court. Minnesota v. D=
ickerson, 508 U.S. 366 (1993).
=20
Or you can quickly read a case brief I wrote in 2006 for my legal analysis =
class listed below I have saved in my email history (read the fact section =
which describes the incident). Isaac
=20
Minnesota v. Dickerson, 508 U.S. 366 (1993).
=20
Procedural History: Dickerson=92s motion to suppress seizure of cocaine evi=
dence was denied by the District Court. As a result Dickerson was found gui=
lty and appealed. The Minnesota Court of Appeals reversed. The State appeal=
ed and the Minnesota Supreme Court affirmed. The U.S. Supreme Court granted=
 certiorari.
=20
Facts: Officers suspicious of Dickerson=92s elusive actions conducted a pat=
down search without a warrant. The search was permitted although it reveale=
d no weapons. While further searching Dickerson one of the officers felt a =
lump in Dickerson=92s jacket pocket. At this point, the officer did not bel=
ieve the lump was a weapon. The officer determined the lump in Dickerson=92=
s jacket was contraband after squeezing, sliding, and manipulating the pock=
et. Dickerson was arrested for possession of a controlled substance.
=20
Issues: (1) Does a protective search to discover weapons go beyond lawful b=
ounds if nonthreatening contraband is seized after no weapons are found?
=20
(2) Is the seizure of contraband obtained by squeezing, sliding, and manipu=
lating Dickerson=92s pocket permitted as evidence after a protective search=
 determined no weapons?=20
=20
Holdings: (1) Yes, (2) No
=20
Analysis: The Fourth Amendment protects "against unreasonable searches and =
seizures" barring a protective search to discover weapons without a warrant=
 based on reasonable suspicion. U.S.C.A. Const.Amend. 4. A search and seizu=
re to discover weapons is permitted without a warrant with reasonable suspi=
cion known as a Terry search. Terry v. Ohio, 392 U.S. 1 (1968). However, if=
 the search and seizure goes beyond what is necessary to discover weapons o=
r contraband its fruits will be suppressed. It is lawful by application of =
analogy during a Terry search to seize contraband other than weapons under =
the "plain view" doctrine through the sense of touch. Michigan v. Long, 463=
 U.S. 1032 (1983). The officer conducting the Terry search determined Dicke=
rson was not armed, however, the officer discovered a lump in Dickerson=92s=
 pocket. The officer did not immediately recognize the lump as contraband. =
In this case, contraband was obtained after searching Dickerson=92s pockets=
 by squeezing, sliding, and manipulating outside the lawful bounds of a Ter=
ry search.
=20
Holding: The U.S. Supreme Court affirmed judgement to suppress seizure of e=
vidence.

----- Original Message ----- 
From: "Isaac" <greylane@hotmail.com>
To: <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
Sent: Tuesday, March 25, 2008 2:21 PM
Subject: RE: [sfraves] NRR: Police search homes for guns in DC - 
ILLEGAL/UNETHICAL?



Good article Marco nice statement Philip I think everyone on this list knows 
something or has something to add by experience or hearsay. Letting a police 
officer search your home or car with your consent and no warrant is legal 
but you are asking for troulbe if you agree and have something illegal in 
your home or car.

In college we use to debate this topic in class when I was writing my senior 
thesis as an undergrad. We all know that if an officer does not have a 
warrant and has to ask then they do not have enough probable cause to 
conduct the search. Although here is the catch that mostly applies to people 
in automobiles.

Police pressure people and use many different tactics to persuade people to 
conduct a search by asking them making it legal. I read a great case and I 
recommend anyone with enough time on there hands to read it because it sets 
the precedent for illegal searches with the Supreme Court. Minnesota v. 
Dickerson, 508 U.S. 366 (1993).

Or you can quickly read a case brief I wrote in 2006 for my legal analysis 
class listed below I have saved in my email history (read the fact section 
which describes the incident). Isaac

Minnesota v. Dickerson, 508 U.S. 366 (1993).

Procedural History: Dickersons motion to suppress seizure of cocaine 
evidence was denied by the District Court. As a result Dickerson was found 
guilty and appealed. The Minnesota Court of Appeals reversed. The State 
appealed and the Minnesota Supreme Court affirmed. The U.S. Supreme Court 
granted certiorari.

Facts: Officers suspicious of Dickersons elusive actions conducted a 
patdown search without a warrant. The search was permitted although it 
revealed no weapons. While further searching Dickerson one of the officers 
felt a lump in Dickersons jacket pocket. At this point, the officer did not 
believe the lump was a weapon. The officer determined the lump in Dickersons 
jacket was contraband after squeezing, sliding, and manipulating the pocket. 
Dickerson was arrested for possession of a controlled substance.

Issues: (1) Does a protective search to discover weapons go beyond lawful 
bounds if nonthreatening contraband is seized after no weapons are found?

(2) Is the seizure of contraband obtained by squeezing, sliding, and 
manipulating Dickersons pocket permitted as evidence after a protective 
search determined no weapons?

Holdings: (1) Yes, (2) No

Analysis: The Fourth Amendment protects "against unreasonable searches and 
seizures" barring a protective search to discover weapons without a warrant 
based on reasonable suspicion. U.S.C.A. Const.Amend. 4. A search and seizure 
to discover weapons is permitted without a warrant with reasonable suspicion 
known as a Terry search. Terry v. Ohio, 392 U.S. 1 (1968). However, if the 
search and seizure goes beyond what is necessary to discover weapons or 
contraband its fruits will be suppressed. It is lawful by application of 
analogy during a Terry search to seize contraband other than weapons under 
the "plain view" doctrine through the sense of touch. Michigan v. Long, 463 
U.S. 1032 (1983). The officer conducting the Terry search determined 
Dickerson was not armed, however, the officer discovered a lump in Dickersons 
pocket. The officer did not immediately recognize the lump as contraband. In 
this case, contraband was obtained after searching Dickersons pockets by 
squeezing, sliding, and manipulating outside the lawful bounds of a Terry 
search.

Holding: The U.S. Supreme Court affirmed judgement to suppress seizure of 
evidence.

> got > another complaint and came back, they were giving me a citation.> >

e law with no real definite answer! Read my "analysis" section of my case b=
rief.
=20

s like someone not hiring you for a job because of your race. You would nev=
er know if you were not given that job because of racial discrimination so =
you are right to an extent but the issue goes much deeper with no real answ=
er! The reason why is because the warrant issue is constantly challeged and=
 won by law enforcement. It is also challenged by the person disputing the =
search and prevails from time to time.=20
=20
If law was as easy as reading legal books then there would be no need justi=
ce system to challenge the laws we have. I am an IP Litigation Paralegal so=
 I see a ton of different shit all the time that seems to be wrong but is r=
ight and prevails in court.

Marco read my analysis that I wrote on the Dickerson case. The first few se=
ntences directly apply to your thought train. Just so you know these laws c=
an be challenged and interpreted differently depending on the case... Each =
sentence that I wrote is backed up by specific precedent and various laws.
=20
Isaac
=20
Analysis: The Fourth Amendment protects "against unreasonable searches and =
seizures" barring a protective search to discover weapons without a warrant=
 based on reasonable suspicion. U.S.C.A. Const.Amend. 4. A search and seizu=
re to discover weapons is permitted without a warrant with reasonable suspi=
cion known as a Terry search. Terry v. Ohio, 392 U.S. 1 (1968). However, if=
 the search and seizure goes beyond what is necessary to discover weapons o=
r contraband its fruits will be suppressed. It is lawful by application of =
analogy during a Terry search to seize contraband other than weapons under =
the "plain view" doctrine through the sense of touch. Michigan v. Long, 463=
 U.S. 1032 (1983). The officer conducting the Terry search determined Dicke=
rson was not armed, however, the officer discovered a lump in Dickerson=92s=
 pocket. The officer did not immediately recognize the lump as contraband. =
In this case, contraband was obtained after searching Dickerson=92s pockets=
 by squeezing, sliding, and manipulating outside the lawful bounds of a Ter=
ry search.
=20
> From: greylane@hotmail.com> To: sfraves@hyperreal.org> Date: Tue, 25 Mar =
2008 14:21:54 -0700> Subject: RE: [sfraves] NRR: Police search homes for gu=
ns in DC - ILLEGAL/UNETHICAL?> > > Good article Marco nice statement Philip=
 I think everyone on this list knows something or has something to add by e=
xperience or hearsay. Letting a police officer search your home or car with=
 your consent and no warrant is legal but you are asking for troulbe if you=
 agree and have something illegal in your home or car. > > In college we us=
e to debate this topic in class when I was writing my senior thesis as an u=
ndergrad. We all know that if an officer does not have a warrant and has to=
 ask then they do not have enough probable cause to conduct the search. Alt=
hough here is the catch that mostly applies to people in automobiles. > > P=
olice pressure people and use many different tactics to persuade people to =
conduct a search by asking them making it legal. I read a great case and I =
recommend anyone with enough time on there hands to read it because it sets=
 the precedent for illegal searches with the Supreme Court. Minnesota v. Di=
ckerson, 508 U.S. 366 (1993).> > Or you can quickly read a case brief I wro=
te in 2006 for my legal analysis class listed below I have saved in my emai=
l history (read the fact section which describes the incident). Isaac> > Mi=
nnesota v. Dickerson, 508 U.S. 366 (1993).> > Procedural History: Dickerson=
=92s motion to suppress seizure of cocaine evidence was denied by the Distr=
ict Court. As a result Dickerson was found guilty and appealed. The Minneso=
ta Court of Appeals reversed. The State appealed and the Minnesota Supreme =
Court affirmed. The U.S. Supreme Court granted certiorari.> > Facts: Office=
rs suspicious of Dickerson=92s elusive actions conducted a patdown search w=
ithout a warrant. The search was permitted although it revealed no weapons.=
 While further searching Dickerson one of the officers felt a lump in Dicke=
rson=92s jacket pocket. At this point, the officer did not believe the lump=
 was a weapon. The officer determined the lump in Dickerson=92s jacket was =
contraband after squeezing, sliding, and manipulating the pocket. Dickerson=
 was arrested for possession of a controlled substance.> > Issues: (1) Does=
 a protective search to discover weapons go beyond lawful bounds if nonthre=
atening contraband is seized after no weapons are found?> > (2) Is the seiz=
ure of contraband obtained by squeezing, sliding, and manipulating Dickerso=
n=92s pocket permitted as evidence after a protective search determined no =
weapons? > > Holdings: (1) Yes, (2) No> > Analysis: The Fourth Amendment pr=
otects "against unreasonable searches and seizures" barring a protective se=
arch to discover weapons without a warrant based on reasonable suspicion. U=
.S.C.A. Const.Amend. 4. A search and seizure to discover weapons is permitt=
ed without a warrant with reasonable suspicion known as a Terry search. Ter=
ry v. Ohio, 392 U.S. 1 (1968). However, if the search and seizure goes beyo=
nd what is necessary to discover weapons or contraband its fruits will be s=
uppressed. It is lawful by application of analogy during a Terry search to =
seize contraband other than weapons under the "plain view" doctrine through=
 the sense of touch. Michigan v. Long, 463 U.S. 1032 (1983). The officer co=
nducting the Terry search determined Dickerson was not armed, however, the =
officer discovered a lump in Dickerson=92s pocket. The officer did not imme=
diately recognize the lump as contraband. In this case, contraband was obta=
ined after searching Dickerson=92s pockets by squeezing, sliding, and manip=
ulating outside the lawful bounds of a Terry search.> > Holding: The U.S. S=
upreme Court affirmed judgement to suppress seizure of evidence.> > > > > F=

----- Original Message ----- 
From: "Isaac" <greylane@hotmail.com>
To: <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
Sent: Tuesday, March 25, 2008 2:57 PM
Subject: RE: [sfraves] NRR: Police search homes for guns in DC - 
ILLEGAL/UNETHICAL?



Marco lets just say that type of search is a very murky gray area within the 
law with no real definite answer! Read my "analysis" section of my case 
brief.

Probable cause is also very sketchy to challenge in some cases because it is 
like someone not hiring you for a job because of your race. You would never 
know if you were not given that job because of racial discrimination so you 
are right to an extent but the issue goes much deeper with no real answer! 
The reason why is because the warrant issue is constantly challeged and won 
by law enforcement. It is also challenged by the person disputing the search 
and prevails from time to time.

If law was as easy as reading legal books then there would be no need 
justice system to challenge the laws we have. I am an IP Litigation 
Paralegal so I see a ton of different shit all the time that seems to be 
wrong but is right and prevails in court.


If it looks like a duck and walks like a duck then it is probably a duck...


Isaac

> From: "Isaac" <greylane@hotmail.com>> To: <sfraves@hyperreal.org>> Sent: 
> Tuesday, March 25, 2008 2:21 PM> Subject: RE: [sfraves] NRR: Police search 
> homes for guns in DC - > ILLEGAL/UNETHICAL?> > > > Good article Marco nice 
> statement Philip I think everyone on this list knows > something or has 
> something to add by experience or hearsay. Letting a police > officer 
> search your home or car with your consent and no warrant is legal > but 
> you are asking for troulbe if you agree and have something illegal in > 
> your home or car.> > In college we use to debate this topic in class when 
> I was writing my senior > thesis as an undergrad. We all know that if an 
> officer does not have a > warrant and has to ask then they do not have 
> enough probable cause to > conduct the search. Although here is the catch 
> that mostly applies to people > in automobiles.> > Police pressure people 
> and use many different tactics to persuade people to > conduct a search by 
> asking them making it legal. I read a great case and I > recommend anyone 
> with enough time on there hands to read it because it sets > the precedent 
> for illegal searches with the Supreme Court. Minnesota v. > Dickerson, 508 
> U.S. 366 (1993).> > Or you can quickly read a case brief I wrote in 2006 
> for my legal analysis > class listed below I have saved in my email 
> history (read the fact section > which describes the incident). Isaac> > 
> Minnesota v. Dickerson, 508 U.S. 366 (1993).> > Procedural History: 
> Dickersons motion to suppress seizure of cocaine > evidence was denied by 
> the District Court. As a result Dickerson was found > guilty and appealed. 
> The Minnesota Court of Appeals reversed. The State > appealed and the 
> Minnesota Supreme Court affirmed. The U.S. Supreme Court > granted 
> certiorari.> > Facts: Officers suspicious of Dickersons elusive actions 
> conducted a > patdown search without a warrant. The search was permitted 
> although it > revealed no weapons. While further searching Dickerson one 
> of the officers > felt a lump in Dickersons jacket pocket. At this point, 
> the officer did not > believe the lump was a weapon. The officer 
> determined the lump in Dickersons > jacket was contraband after 
> squeezing, sliding, and manipulating the pocket. > Dickerson was arrested 
> for possession of a controlled substance.> > Issues: (1) Does a protective 
> search to discover weapons go beyond lawful > bounds if nonthreatening 
> contraband is seized after no weapons are found?> > (2) Is the seizure of 
> contraband obtained by squeezing, sliding, and > manipulating Dickersons 
> pocket permitted as evidence after a protective > search determined no 
> weapons?> > Holdings: (1) Yes, (2) No> > Analysis: The Fourth Amendment 
> protects "against unreasonable searches and > seizures" barring a 
> protective search to discover weapons without a warrant > based on 
> reasonable suspicion. U.S.C.A. Const.Amend. 4. A search and seizure > to 
> discover weapons is permitted without a warrant with reasonable suspicion 
>  > known as a Terry search. Terry v. Ohio, 392 U.S. 1 (1968). However, if 
> the > search and seizure goes beyond what is necessary to discover weapons 
> or > contraband its fruits will be suppressed. It is lawful by application 
> of > analogy during a Terry search to seize contraband other than weapons 
> under > the "plain view" doctrine through the sense of touch. Michigan v. 
> Long, 463 > U.S. 1032 (1983). The officer conducting the Terry search 
> determined > Dickerson was not armed, however, the officer discovered a 
> lump in Dickersons > pocket. The officer did not immediately recognize 
> the lump as contraband. In > this case, contraband was obtained after 
> searching Dickersons pockets by > squeezing, sliding, and manipulating 
> outside the lawful bounds of a Terry > search.> > Holding: The U.S. 
> Supreme Court affirmed judgement to suppress seizure of > evidence.> > > > 
>  > From: st_indigo@earthlink.net> To: sfraves@hyperreal.org> Date: Tue, 25 
>  > > Mar 2008 12:47:38 -0700> Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: Police search 
> homes > > for guns in DC - ILLEGAL/UNETHICAL?> > this is a good time to 
> remind you > > all - DO NOT EVER let the po-po in > unless they have a 
> warrant, or unless > > you were the one who called > them! this also goes 
> for event venues.> > if > > they show up at your event, lock the door 
> behind you (have a secret > > > knock set up ahead of time), go outside 
> and chat. make sure you have > > > I.D. on you. if there was a noise 
> complaint made, offer to turn the > > > music down.> > i've done this 
> twice, and it has worked the same way both > > times. the > cops took down 
> my info, gave me a warning, and said if they > > got > another complaint 
> and came back, they were giving me a citation.> > > > it's important that

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Nrr: XM-Sirius merger approved by DOJ

As a former competitor of sorts of both XM and Sirius when I was at Live365, I can say that it is very unlikely that anyone else will launch satellites to compete with the merged company.  These satellite constellations cost billions to launch and the revenue resulting from neither of the companies at the present time really justifies the expense. 

The only competition likely to arise in the short run is from wireless broadband Internet which (at least in the short term) will be delivered by cellular networks rather than satellites.  

Note however satellite radio has a very favorable rate position compared with Internet radio offerings...

Regards,

Peter

Police search homes for guns in DC - ILLEGAL/UNETHICAL?=0A=0A=0AGood articl=
e Marco nice statement Philip I think everyone on this list knows something=
 or has something to add by experience or hearsay. Letting a police officer=
 search your home or car with your consent and no warrant is legal but you =
are asking for troulbe if you agree and have something illegal in your home=
 or car. =0A=0AIn college we use to debate this topic in class when I was w=
riting my senior thesis as an undergrad. We all know that if an officer doe=
s not have a warrant and has to ask then they do not have enough probable c=
ause to conduct the search. Although here is the catch that mostly applies =
to people in automobiles. =0A=0APolice pressure people and use many differe=
nt tactics to persuade people to conduct a search by asking them making it =
legal. I read a great case and I recommend anyone with enough time on there=
 hands to read it because it sets the precedent for illegal searches with t=
he Supreme Court. Minnesota v. Dickerson, 508 U.S. 366 (1993).=0A=0AOr you =
can quickly read a case brief I wrote in 2006 for my legal analysis class l=
isted below I have saved in my email history (read the fact section which d=
escribes the incident). Isaac=0A=0AMinnesota v. Dickerson, 508 U.S. 366 (19=
93).=0A=0AProcedural History: Dickerson=E2=80=99s motion to suppress seizur=
e of cocaine evidence was denied by the District Court. As a result Dickers=
on was found guilty and appealed. The Minnesota Court of Appeals reversed. =
The State appealed and the Minnesota Supreme Court affirmed. The U.S. Supre=
me Court granted certiorari.=0A=0AFacts: Officers suspicious of Dickerson=
=E2=80=99s elusive actions conducted a patdown search without a warrant. Th=
e search was permitted although it revealed no weapons. While further searc=
hing Dickerson one of the officers felt a lump in Dickerson=E2=80=99s jacke=
t pocket. At this point, the officer did not believe the lump was a weapon.=
 The officer determined the lump in Dickerson=E2=80=99s jacket was contraba=
nd after squeezing, sliding, and manipulating the pocket. Dickerson was arr=
ested for possession of a controlled substance.=0A=0AIssues: (1) Does a pro=
tective search to discover weapons go beyond lawful bounds if nonthreatenin=
g contraband is seized after no weapons are found?=0A=0A(2) Is the seizure =
of contraband obtained by squeezing, sliding, and manipulating Dickerson=E2=
=80=99s pocket permitted as evidence after a protective search determined n=
o weapons? =0A=0AHoldings: (1) Yes, (2) No=0A=0AAnalysis: The Fourth Amendm=
ent protects "against unreasonable searches and seizures" barring a protect=
ive search to discover weapons without a warrant based on reasonable suspic=
ion. U.S.C.A. Const.Amend. 4. A search and seizure to discover weapons is p=
ermitted without a warrant with reasonable suspicion known as a Terry searc=
h. Terry v. Ohio, 392 U.S. 1 (1968). However, if the search and seizure goe=
s beyond what is necessary to discover weapons or contraband its fruits wil=
l be suppressed. It is lawful by application of analogy during a Terry sear=
ch to seize contraband other than weapons under the "plain view" doctrine t=
hrough the sense of touch. Michigan v. Long, 463 U.S. 1032 (1983). The offi=
cer conducting the Terry search determined Dickerson was not armed, however=
, the officer discovered a lump in Dickerson=E2=80=99s pocket. The officer =
did not immediately recognize the lump as contraband. In this case, contrab=
and was obtained after searching Dickerson=E2=80=99s
 pockets by squeezing, sliding, and manipulating outside the lawful bounds =
of a Terry search.=0A=0AHolding: The U.S. Supreme Court affirmed judgement =
to suppress seizure of evidence.=0A  =0A=0A=0A> From: st_indigo@earthlink.n=

Subject: [sfraves] NRR: Economic Depression? Naw... (was Re: [sfraves] (nrr) QOD (Tue))

I go on vacation for a couple of days and you guys have all the fun without me?

I'd say the probability of a serious economic depression in the United States is actually pretty low, but of course not zero.  Be careful what you wish for however.  Conspiracy fuckwads such as Jeff Rense are not a very good source of information here.  Rense has been yelling "depression" at everry economic downturn since he's been on the air. One almost imagines he's wishing for it to happen.  I guess this is just another item on Rense's extensive menu of fear and hate, but its also worth remembering that the events of the Great Depression were triggered by a panic as well as an actual economic event.

Anyway most of these low budget analyses are flawed by failing to understand the differences between the economic systems operating in the 1920s and 30s as compared to what we see today.  There's the little detail of unemployment remaining under 5% of course.  But you'll probably hear a lot more about the differences in the regulatory regimes in the press.  However the biggest difference IMO is global connectivity of economic systems.  If a serious depression were to hit the U.S., would you really be better off somewhere else?  Other than perhaps Europe, the answer is probably no.

To understand what I am talking about it is worth reviewing another news story this week that got a lot less attention than the housing collapse and resulting fiscal instability: Honduran cantelopes.  The FDA recently announced that a number of people had been sickened by Salmonella contaminaiton possibly resulting from eating cantelopes.  Fear of a drop in demand for melons prompted the president of the Honduras to issue a statement decrying the FDA's rash announcement. That is, even the threat of a reduction in demand from the U.S., not even an actual reduction in demand, was enough to prompt the leader of another nation to issue a public statement.  That's a good indication of just how big our markets (and supermarkets) are compared to the rest of the world.

The truth is if that the U.S. entered a depression, the world economy as a whole would probably collapse.  People would starve world wide and the U.S. might very well see the least of it.  Consider the global effect of a sudden and nearly complete drop in U.S. demand for consumer electronics for example.

As another example, consider the cost of the war in Iraq.  We've all taken on a significant debt as the result of the Bush administration's war in Iraq.  But its worth asking where exactly we borrowed this much money?  The answer is in large part China.  China opposed the Iraq war in the U.N. and in their public statements but at the same time loaned the U.S. the money to fight the war in the first place.  It is unclear we even could have fought the war without these loans.  Not everything is as it appears in U.S. Today perhaps.

And if the U.S. where to default on these loans, who'd be worse off the U.S. or China?  I think that this is quite unclear and therefore its simply not going to be allowed to happen by either party.  Its a new more evolved form of Mutually Assured Destruction.

Finally, in conclusion, listen to what Philip has to say here about preparing yourself somehow because if you are all correct about the future of our economy simply whining about it on the Internets won't be of much use to you.

Best,

Peter

PS

Cable Recordings and Shine present:

*~*CABLE WEDNESDAYS*~*

Every 2nd and 4th Wednesday @ SHINE
9pm - 2am
21+

funkysleazydirtygroovybanginspacediscohouseandbreaks

03/26/08 Edition:

Special Guest DJ's:
Formless (Flytrap / Day of Hugs / Bete Noire - UK)

Dan Jones is a London based DJ and producer with a long-standing passion for 
underground house music. Djing and producing under the name Formless, he has 
been rocking clubs around London with a blend of forward thinking tech house 
and dirty electro beats.
In the last 12 months he has been creating a buzz with his unique, 
energetic, upfront sound at respected London venues like The Cross, 
Turnmills, Pacha, The Key and The Island. His brisk ascent through the DJ 
ranks came on the back of a number of DJ mix competition wins and playing a 
live set on MoS Radio. This gave the exposure needed to push his sound onto 
bigger dancefloors. Having consolidated his position in London, Formless is 
now taking his music to the international club scene.

With more dates in San Francisco, Sydney, Brisbane and the Ukraine on the 
horizon, time in the studio working on a new solo EP and a number of remixes 
and collaborations, the future looks bright for one of djing's freshest 
talents. On top of DJ and production commitments Dan has just launched his 
own night Flytrap, already hosting parties at The Cross, The Island & Pacha 
London. He still finds time every summer to co-ordinate the music for the 
Norgstock Festival (nr. Stonehenge) and run his own Day of Hugs bi-annual 
Manor House Party (nr. Bournemouth).

also playing:

The Vinyl Whore (High On Hope - SF)

w/ Residents:
Justin Johnson (Cable Recordings / Barely Legal Records / Kingsize-USA - 
NYC/SF)
Marc(O) (OtherWorld / Cable Wednesdays / The MidnightSons - DC/SF )

NO COVER!!!!
2 for 1 Smirnoff drinks!!!!
Free photo booth from FLICKR!!!!!

1337 Mission Street (between 9th & 10th)

As a former competitor of sorts of both XM and Sirius when I was at Live365,
I can say that it is very unlikely that anyone else will launch satellites
to compete with the merged company.  These satellite constellations cost
billions to launch and the revenue resulting from neither of the companies
at the present time really justifies the expense. 

The only competition likely to arise in the short run is from wireless
broadband Internet which (at least in the short term) will be delivered by
cellular networks rather than satellites.  

Note however satellite radio has a very favorable rate position compared
with Internet radio offerings...

Regards,

Peter

There are a lot more reasons to lack faith in the current economy than to
have faith in it. We're looking at the US moving from a manufacturing based
economy to a service based economy. This is to say, instead of making
things, we're seeing more and more people working in the service industry.
Those jobs Bush loves to brag about making? Most of them are at places like
Wal-Mart. The infrastructure of this country is rotting out from under our
feet, and on top of it we're running out of oil.

Things ain't lookin too good.

Excellent point about growing your own veggies, though. The less you can
come to rely on globalized infrastructure the better off you'll be when it
starts to collapse.

I myself would be FUCKED if the shit hit the fan tomorrow, since I almost
always eat out and rarely even so much as buy groceries. I need to learn how
to garden or something. FUCK.

On Wed, Mar 26, 2008 at 8:26 AM, <dangrsmind@yahoo.com> wrote:

> I go on vacation for a couple of days and you guys have all the fun
> without me?
>
> I'd say the probability of a serious economic depression in the United
> States is actually pretty low, but of course not zero.  Be careful what you
> wish for however.  Conspiracy fuckwads such as Jeff Rense are not a very
> good source of information here.  Rense has been yelling "depression" at
> everry economic downturn since he's been on the air. One almost imagines
> he's wishing for it to happen.  I guess this is just another item on Rense's
> extensive menu of fear and hate, but its also worth remembering that the
> events of the Great Depression were triggered by a panic as well as an
> actual economic event.
>
> Anyway most of these low budget analyses are flawed by failing to
> understand the differences between the economic systems operating in the
> 1920s and 30s as compared to what we see today.  There's the little detail
> of unemployment remaining under 5% of course.  But you'll probably hear a
> lot more about the differences in the regulatory regimes in the press.
>  However the biggest difference IMO is global connectivity of economic
> systems.  If a serious depression were to hit the U.S., would you really
> be better off somewhere else?  Other than perhaps Europe, the answer is
> probably no.
>
> To understand what I am talking about it is worth reviewing another news
> story this week that got a lot less attention than the housing collapse and
> resulting fiscal instability: Honduran cantelopes.  The FDA recently
> announced that a number of people had been sickened by Salmonella
> contaminaiton possibly resulting from eating cantelopes.  Fear of a drop in
> demand for melons prompted the president of the Honduras to issue a
> statement decrying the FDA's rash announcement. That is, even the threat of
> a reduction in demand from the U.S., not even an actual reduction in
> demand, was enough to prompt the leader of another nation to issue a public
> statement.  That's a good indication of just how big our markets (and
> supermarkets) are compared to the rest of the world.
>
> The truth is if that the U.S. entered a depression, the world economy as a
> whole would probably collapse.  People would starve world wide and the U.S.
> might very well see the least of it.  Consider the global effect of a sudden
> and nearly complete drop in U.S. demand for consumer electronics for
> example.
>
> As another example, consider the cost of the war in Iraq.  We've all taken
> on a significant debt as the result of the Bush administration's war in
> Iraq.  But its worth asking where exactly we borrowed this much money?  The
> answer is in large part China.  China opposed the Iraq war in the U.N. and
> in their public statements but at the same time loaned the U.S. the money
> to fight the war in the first place.  It is unclear we even could have
> fought the war without these loans.  Not everything is as it appears in
> U.S. Today perhaps.
>
> And if the U.S. where to default on these loans, who'd be worse off the
> U.S. or China?  I think that this is quite unclear and therefore its
> simply not going to be allowed to happen by either party.  Its a new more
> evolved form of Mutually Assured Destruction.
>
> Finally, in conclusion, listen to what Philip has to say here about
> preparing yourself somehow because if you are all correct about the future
> of our economy simply whining about it on the Internets won't be of much use
> to you.
>
> Best,
>
> Peter

Saturday, April 5th, 2008


[ K O N T R O L ]


minimal techno + avant-house
every 1st Saturday @ The Endup



featuring from Berlin, Germany:

PAN-POT  ( Mobilee . Einmaleins Musik . Clink . CMYK )

>From the heart of the Berlin underground, Mobilee's
white-hot DJ/production duo Pan-Pot finally grace the
[KONTROL] decks with an extended set of late night
dancefloor dementia. Having recently been chosen to
release the inaugural full length artist album on
Mobilee, "Pan-O-Rama", as well as being nominated for
"Best Minimal Artist" in the 2008 Beatport Awards,
this is your chance to hear firsthand what all the
fuss is about.  Prepare for a night of deep, dark,
surgically precise beats that will have your feet
moving and your head swimming.



plus special guest:


CLINT STEWART  ( Auralism Records . Nightlight Music )

In the last year Auralism assistant label manager
Clint Stewart has transformed before our eyes from
an enthusiastic new face on the scene to a tried and
true staple of SF's burgeoning techno community.
Bear witness to his prodigious talent with a highly
anticipated set in which Clint promises to "beat it
like a red-headed stepchild!"



with [KONTROL] residents:


ALLAND BYALLO  ( Leibe*Detail . Nightlight Music )
NIKOLA BAYTALA  ( Robsoul . S.W.A.T. )
SAMMY D  ( Dirtybird . Utensil )
CRAIG KUNA  ( Platform . ESDJCO )
