PAN-POT

A pan-pot is a simple, workaday knob, given to side-to-side flip-flopping
and not much else. Pan-Pot, on the other hand, are a brilliantly
multidimensional Berlin duo currently twisting house and techno fans into
rapturous fits.

In just a few short years, Pan-Pot--the duo comprised of Tassilo Ippenberge=
r
and Thomas Benedix=97-have become a central presence in electronic dance
music's most advanced sectors. Their rise parallels that of their home
label, Anja Schneider's Mobilee, coming at a time when established
categories are breaking down and accepted notions of "minimal" (please) are
giving way to an unprecedented degree of dynamism on demanding dancefloors.

Pan-Pot's vinyl debut came in May 2005 with the Popy & Caste EP
(mobilee002), featuring two cuts bursting with gritty, dirty funk, as thoug=
h
they'd scraped all the gunk from beneath the knobs of their gear, packed it
into a ball and sent it rolling across the nightclub. Since then, in
addition to their contribution to the Extra EP (mobilee005 plus), backing
Daniel Stefanik's anthemic banger "The Bells," they've released three more
EPs on Mobilee (Obscenity, mobilee005; Black Lodge, mobilee012; and What Is
What, mobilee023) and two on Einmaleins Musik. Their kinetic, undulating
grooves have proved particularly tempting to other producers=97-Jesse Rose,
Lee Van Dowski, Agn=E8s, Barem and Camea have all taken (pot)shots at
reworking the group's tunes=97-and their own remixing skills are increasing=
ly
in demand: Pan- Pot have put their immediately recognizable spin on tracks
by Misc., Anja Schneider & Sebo K, Tim Xavier, Dapayk Solo, Sweet 'n Candy,
and Dami=E1n Schwartz, among others.

The release of their debut album marks yet another milestone for the group.
Appropriately titled Pan-O-Rama, the record=97-which has the honor of being
the first artist album released on Mobilee=97-offers a 360-degree tour of
techno at its most twisted, balancing ominous atmospherics with an unusual
lightness of touch, and running classic machine music through silicon's
digital wringer.

They may name themselves after a piece of gear, but Pan-Pot's music is
ultimately about moving bodies, not knobs. Both live and as DJs, Pan-Pot
deliver on that promise with sets that rope together crisply minimal, cooll=
y
restrained techno and hot and heavy house. Anyone who's ever played with an
analog synthesizer knows that all those pots and dials are there to be
touched; Pan-Pot reaches out and touches right back=97with a love slap from
the heart of the Berlin underground.

_______________________________________________


CLINT STEWART

In a sea of heads, Clint Stewart can't contain his enthusiasm. "It's an
amazing time for dance music," says the Auralism assistant label manager.
"There's so much good music and an endless list of people making it. It's
inspiring." The Florida-born DJ / producer / promoter is true to his word,
commanding crowds with ease and producing sexy, gauzy cuts that exhort
everyone to dance.

Growing up in a home surrounded by the sounds of classical music to classic
rock and early blues, he began training in classical piano and guitar. Over
time Stewart's adolescent obsession with punk's passion and aggression ("I
hated dance music") led to a college-age awakening to techno's dark,
relentless groove. A stint on UNF College Radio Station gave him the
opportunity to start Nocturnal Underground radio show where he met Marc
Smith. After college he moved to Miami and began eventually joining forces
with Auralism co-founders Marc Smith and Jason Short and playing at their
residency at Jazid. Within the year, Stewart moved to Hawaii for a brief
stint to "get away", but was soon living in San Francisco after a gig in
which he never stepped foot on his return flight.

Since joining the Auralism camp, Stewart has been "going 100 miles an hour,
all day, every day," playing high-profile DJ gigs with top artists among as
well as a particularly sizzling set at SF's annual LoveFest. In addition
pounding the pavement for Auralism, Stewart has a growing list of
productions out there, including a pair of ecstatic remixes for the label's
inaugural Aural Therapy 1.1 compilation. That's a lot of work for a short
time in a new town, but master multi-tasker Stewart's just getting started.


---> LINKS:

Saturday, April 5th, 2008


[ K O N T R O L ]


minimal techno + avant-house
every 1st Saturday @ The Endup



featuring from Berlin, Germany:

PAN-POT  ( Mobilee . Einmaleins Musik . Clink . CMYK )

>From the heart of the Berlin underground, Mobilee's
white-hot DJ/production duo Pan-Pot finally grace the
[KONTROL] decks with an extended set of late night
dancefloor dementia. Having recently been chosen to
release the inaugural full length artist album on
Mobilee, "Pan-O-Rama", as well as being nominated for
"Best Minimal Artist" in the 2008 Beatport Awards,
this is your chance to hear firsthand what all the
fuss is about.  Prepare for a night of deep, dark,
surgically precise beats that will have your feet
moving and your head swimming.



plus special guest:


CLINT STEWART  ( Auralism Records . Nightlight Music )

In the last year Auralism assistant label manager
Clint Stewart has transformed before our eyes from
an enthusiastic new face on the scene to a tried and
true staple of SF's burgeoning techno community.
Bear witness to his prodigious talent with a highly
anticipated set in which Clint promises to "beat it
like a red-headed stepchild!"



with [KONTROL] residents:


ALLAND BYALLO  ( Leibe*Detail . Nightlight Music )
NIKOLA BAYTALA  ( Robsoul . S.W.A.T. )
SAMMY D  ( Dirtybird . Utensil )
CRAIG KUNA  ( Platform . ESDJCO )


________________________________________________


The ENDUP
401 6th St @ Harrison, SF
10pm - 6am / 21+ / $15
http://www.theendup.com

FREE until 11pm!

________________________________________________


PAN-POT

A pan-pot is a simple, workaday knob, given to side-to-side flip-flopping
and not much else. Pan-Pot, on the other hand, are a brilliantly
multidimensional Berlin duo currently twisting house and techno fans into
rapturous fits.

In just a few short years, Pan-Pot--the duo comprised of Tassilo Ippenberger
and Thomas Benedix-have become a central presence in electronic dance
music's most advanced sectors. Their rise parallels that of their home
label, Anja Schneider's Mobilee, coming at a time when established
categories are breaking down and accepted notions of "minimal" (please) are
giving way to an unprecedented degree of dynamism on demanding dancefloors.

Pan-Pot's vinyl debut came in May 2005 with the Popy & Caste EP
(mobilee002), featuring two cuts bursting with gritty, dirty funk, as though
they'd scraped all the gunk from beneath the knobs of their gear, packed it
into a ball and sent it rolling across the nightclub. Since then, in
addition to their contribution to the Extra EP (mobilee005 plus), backing
Daniel Stefanik's anthemic banger "The Bells," they've released three more
EPs on Mobilee (Obscenity, mobilee005; Black Lodge, mobilee012; and What Is
What, mobilee023) and two on Einmaleins Musik. Their kinetic, undulating
grooves have proved particularly tempting to other producers-Jesse Rose,
Lee Van Dowski, Agns, Barem and Camea have all taken (pot)shots at
reworking the group's tunes-and their own remixing skills are increasingly
in demand: Pan- Pot have put their immediately recognizable spin on tracks
by Misc., Anja Schneider & Sebo K, Tim Xavier, Dapayk Solo, Sweet 'n Candy,
and Damin Schwartz, among others.

The release of their debut album marks yet another milestone for the group.
Appropriately titled Pan-O-Rama, the record-which has the honor of being
the first artist album released on Mobilee-offers a 360-degree tour of
techno at its most twisted, balancing ominous atmospherics with an unusual
lightness of touch, and running classic machine music through silicon's
digital wringer.

They may name themselves after a piece of gear, but Pan-Pot's music is
ultimately about moving bodies, not knobs. Both live and as DJs, Pan-Pot
deliver on that promise with sets that rope together crisply minimal, coolly
restrained techno and hot and heavy house. Anyone who's ever played with an
analog synthesizer knows that all those pots and dials are there to be
touched; Pan-Pot reaches out and touches right backwith a love slap from
the heart of the Berlin underground.


---> LINKS:

Mobilee Website:
http://mobilee-records.de/pan-pot

Pan-Pot on MySpace:
http://www.myspace.com/panpot

Pan-Pot's Discography:
http://www.discogs.com/artist/Pan-Pot

_______________________________________________


CLINT STEWART

In a sea of heads, Clint Stewart can't contain his enthusiasm. "It's an
amazing time for dance music," says the Auralism assistant label manager.
"There's so much good music and an endless list of people making it. It's
inspiring." The Florida-born DJ / producer / promoter is true to his word,
commanding crowds with ease and producing sexy, gauzy cuts that exhort
everyone to dance.

Growing up in a home surrounded by the sounds of classical music to classic
rock and early blues, he began training in classical piano and guitar. Over
time Stewart's adolescent obsession with punk's passion and aggression ("I
hated dance music") led to a college-age awakening to techno's dark,
relentless groove. A stint on UNF College Radio Station gave him the
opportunity to start Nocturnal Underground radio show where he met Marc
Smith. After college he moved to Miami and began eventually joining forces
with Auralism co-founders Marc Smith and Jason Short and playing at their
residency at Jazid. Within the year, Stewart moved to Hawaii for a brief
stint to "get away", but was soon living in San Francisco after a gig in
which he never stepped foot on his return flight.

Since joining the Auralism camp, Stewart has been "going 100 miles an hour,
all day, every day," playing high-profile DJ gigs with top artists among as
well as a particularly sizzling set at SF's annual LoveFest. In addition
pounding the pavement for Auralism, Stewart has a growing list of
productions out there, including a pair of ecstatic remixes for the label's
inaugural Aural Therapy 1.1 compilation. That's a lot of work for a short
time in a new town, but master multi-tasker Stewart's just getting started.


---> LINKS:

Auralism Website:
http://www.auralismrecords.com/

Clint on MySpace:
http://www.myspace.com/clintstewartsounds


---> AUDIO:

Clint Stewart's Comfort Sessions Mix, 2007:
http://www.kontrolsf.com/K34/clint_stewart_-_comfort_sessions_sept_07.mp3


---> VIDEO:

Clint Stewart @ LoveFest 2007:
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QDtTb4FSu3I

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: Economic Depression? Naw... (was Re: [sfraves] 
     (nrr) QOD (Tue))

Remember that just because manufacturing jobs have been shipped overseas
does not make us dependent on imports like all the sensationalist
"pundits" like to make us think. The USA is the richist country in the
world in terms of readily-available natural resources. The only thing we
really must import is fuel. I agree that we are heavily dependent on this.
However, we are not dependent on importing stuff like food, which China is
for example. We can grow our own food, mine our own ore, and cut our own
timber. China cannot. This is one thing a lot of people fail to mention
when discussing our debt with China: China needs us a helluva lot more
than we need them. If things start to become too costly for us to import,
we'll simply see a return of domestic manufacturing.

Also, there is nothing wrong with a service-based economy (the Netherlands
is a perfect example) as long as wages keep pace with the price of goods
and services.

The problem now is our runaway inflation and dependence on oil. The
inflation has been deliberately engineered by Bush as a stealth tax in
order to pay for the war that Bush has waged. Bush Co. and the Fed have
been deliberately devaluing the dollar so the deficit isn't as large. Bush
is our real problem. Look at the deficit before his term, WE HAD NONE,
even with massive importation of Chinese goods.

Inflation would be nowhere near what it is right now without Bush
literally funding the military industrial complex by using the Fed to
print their own money.

> There are a lot more reasons to lack faith in the current economy than to
> have faith in it. We're looking at the US moving from a manufacturing
> based
> economy to a service based economy. This is to say, instead of making
> things, we're seeing more and more people working in the service industry.
> Those jobs Bush loves to brag about making? Most of them are at places
> like
> Wal-Mart. The infrastructure of this country is rotting out from under our
> feet, and on top of it we're running out of oil.
>
> Things ain't lookin too good.
>
> Excellent point about growing your own veggies, though. The less you can
> come to rely on globalized infrastructure the better off you'll be when it
> starts to collapse.
>
> I myself would be FUCKED if the shit hit the fan tomorrow, since I almost
> always eat out and rarely even so much as buy groceries. I need to learn
> how
> to garden or something. FUCK.

> Remember that just because manufacturing jobs have been shipped overseas
> does not make us dependent on imports like all the sensationalist
> "pundits" like to make us think. The USA is the richist country in the
> world in terms of readily-available natural resources. The only thing we
> really must import is fuel. I agree that we are heavily dependent on this.
> However, we are not dependent on importing stuff like food, which China is
> for example. We can grow our own food, mine our own ore, and cut our own
> timber. China cannot. This is one thing a lot of people fail to mention
> when discussing our debt with China: China needs us a helluva lot more
> than we need them. If things start to become too costly for us to import,
> we'll simply see a return of domestic manufacturing.
>
> Also, there is nothing wrong with a service-based economy (the Netherlands
> is a perfect example) as long as wages keep pace with the price of goods
> and services.
>
> The problem now is our runaway inflation and dependence on oil. The
> inflation has been deliberately engineered by Bush as a stealth tax in
> order to pay for the war that Bush has waged. Bush Co. and the Fed have
> been deliberately devaluing the dollar so the deficit isn't as large. Bush
> is our real problem. Look at the deficit before his term, WE HAD NONE,
> even with massive importation of Chinese goods.
>
> Inflation would be nowhere near what it is right now without Bush
> literally funding the military industrial complex by using the Fed to
> print their own money.
>
>> There are a lot more reasons to lack faith in the current economy than to
>> have faith in it. We're looking at the US moving from a manufacturing
>> based
>> economy to a service based economy. This is to say, instead of making
>> things, we're seeing more and more people working in the service 
>> industry.
>> Those jobs Bush loves to brag about making? Most of them are at places
>> like
>> Wal-Mart. The infrastructure of this country is rotting out from under 
>> our
>> feet, and on top of it we're running out of oil.
>>
>> Things ain't lookin too good.
>>
>> Excellent point about growing your own veggies, though. The less you can
>> come to rely on globalized infrastructure the better off you'll be when 
>> it
>> starts to collapse.
>>
>> I myself would be FUCKED if the shit hit the fan tomorrow, since I almost

>> how
>> to garden or something. FUCK.

After the uprising of the 17th of June
The Secretary of the Writers Union
Had leaflets distributed in the Stalinallee
Stating that the people
Had thrown away the confidence of the government
And could win it back only
By redoubled efforts. Would it not be easier
In that case for the government
To dissolve the people
And elect another?

- Bertolt Brecht

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Nrr: XM-Sirius merger approved by DOJ + WMC STREAM!

On Wed, Mar 26, 2008 at 09:23:59AM -0700, raphael wrote:
> Yep, I was thinking more of someone already in place with their own sats...
> Some type of major communications network... Throwing a little bandwidth our
> way ;) 

Correct, not many satellite owners, too expensive for smaller operators
compared to just buying transponder space off someone else.  Really,
the lesson of XM/Sirius is that new technologies often start with too
small a market to survive by competing with each other.  Things need
to settle down for a bit to establish/grow the market, then as the
initial, natural monopoly gets unweildy, more nimble competitors spot
those inefficiencies and figure out ways around them.  In a few years
another player might be able to bulk buy surplus satt time (there is
actually almost always some unused transponder space available), or
maybe wireless metro-area wireless will take sufficient root to be
practical for streaming directly to mass-market mobile audio systems.

Anyway, point being that the requisite is to grow the audience first,
and someone will eventually figure out a way to get their money. :)

At 08:26 AM 3/26/2008, dangrsmind@yahoo.com wrote:
>I go on vacation for a couple of days and you guys have all the fun 
>without me?
>
>I'd say the probability of a serious economic depression in the 
>United States is actually pretty low, but of course not zero.  Be 
>careful what you wish for however.  Conspiracy fuckwads such as Jeff 
>Rense are not a very good source of information here.  Rense has 
>been yelling "depression" at everry economic downturn since he's 
>been on the air. One almost imagines he's wishing for it to 
>happen.  I guess this is just another item on Rense's extensive menu 
>of fear and hate, but its also worth remembering that the events of 
>the Great Depression were triggered by a panic as well as an actual 
>economic event.
>
>Anyway most of these low budget analyses are flawed by failing to 
>understand the differences between the economic systems operating in 
>the 1920s and 30s as compared to what we see today.  There's the 
>little detail of unemployment remaining under 5% of course.  But 
>you'll probably hear a lot more about the differences in the 
>regulatory regimes in the press.  However the biggest difference IMO 
>is global connectivity of economic systems.  If a serious depression 
>were to hit the U.S., would you really be better off somewhere 
>else?  Other than perhaps Europe, the answer is probably no.
>
>To understand what I am talking about it is worth reviewing another 
>news story this week that got a lot less attention than the housing 
>collapse and resulting fiscal instability: Honduran cantelopes.  The 
>FDA recently announced that a number of people had been sickened by 
>Salmonella contaminaiton possibly resulting from eating 
>cantelopes.  Fear of a drop in demand for melons prompted the 
>president of the Honduras to issue a statement decrying the FDA's 
>rash announcement. That is, even the threat of a reduction in demand 
>from the U.S., not even an actual reduction in demand, was enough to 
>prompt the leader of another nation to issue a public 
>statement.  That's a good indication of just how big our markets 
>(and supermarkets) are compared to the rest of the world.
>
>The truth is if that the U.S. entered a depression, the world 
>economy as a whole would probably collapse.  People would starve 
>world wide and the U.S. might very well see the least of 
>it.  Consider the global effect of a sudden and nearly complete drop 
>in U.S. demand for consumer electronics for example.
>
>As another example, consider the cost of the war in Iraq.  We've all 
>taken on a significant debt as the result of the Bush 
>administration's war in Iraq.  But its worth asking where exactly we 
>borrowed this much money?  The answer is in large part China.  China 
>opposed the Iraq war in the U.N. and in their public statements but 
>at the same time loaned the U.S. the money to fight the war in the 
>first place.  It is unclear we even could have fought the war 
>without these loans.  Not everything is as it appears in U.S. Today perhaps.
>
>And if the U.S. where to default on these loans, who'd be worse off 
>the U.S. or China?  I think that this is quite unclear and therefore 
>its simply not going to be allowed to happen by either party.  Its a 
>new more evolved form of Mutually Assured Destruction.
>
>Finally, in conclusion, listen to what Philip has to say here about 
>preparing yourself somehow because if you are all correct about the 
>future of our economy simply whining about it on the Internets won't 
>be of much use to you.
>
>Best,
>
>Peter
>
>PS
>

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Nrr: XM-Sirius merger approved by DOJ + WMC STREAM!


Well, there are upgrades in terms of software, but how satellites work is
pretty well known to the engineers that do stuff with em.

Satts don't "hit" moving targets, they simply hit a given coverage zone
(a kidney shaped contour for a given power level).  It's not that the GPS
birds hit the receivers so much as the receivers are designed to track
satellites as the receiver moves.  The same thing works for media in the
form of the Satellite TV that some airlines offer on planes.  It just costs
more as the tracking has to get more responsive.  That dish used for home
is the cheap way since the house doesn't move relative to the satellite,
but marine receivers have long since been in the "affordable" range that
could handle it, and yes, there are the XM/Sirius type receivers that do
something similar, but it's all in the receiving equipment regardless.

The real innovation that makes things possible is changes in signal encoding
to make more efficient use of the bandwidth.  Traditional C-band gives way
to Ku-Band, 4PSK and then 8PSK improve things further.  Many options to
"compress" the stream to fit into a smaller data stream, with only minimal
changes in the big birds themselves up in orbit.


ray

  STREAM!

how does a receiver receive if it's not being hit?  LOL


sarilion

At 08:02 PM 3/26/2008, you wrote:

>Well, there are upgrades in terms of software, but how satellites work is
>pretty well known to the engineers that do stuff with em.
>
>Satts don't "hit" moving targets, they simply hit a given coverage zone
>(a kidney shaped contour for a given power level).  It's not that the GPS
>birds hit the receivers so much as the receivers are designed to track
>satellites as the receiver moves.  The same thing works for media in the
>form of the Satellite TV that some airlines offer on planes.  It just costs
>more as the tracking has to get more responsive.  That dish used for home
>is the cheap way since the house doesn't move relative to the satellite,
>but marine receivers have long since been in the "affordable" range that
>could handle it, and yes, there are the XM/Sirius type receivers that do
>something similar, but it's all in the receiving equipment regardless.
>
>The real innovation that makes things possible is changes in signal encoding
>to make more efficient use of the bandwidth.  Traditional C-band gives way
>to Ku-Band, 4PSK and then 8PSK improve things further.  Many options to
>"compress" the stream to fit into a smaller data stream, with only minimal
>changes in the big birds themselves up in orbit.
>
>
>ray
>
>
>

> >

WMC.

many people are holding it down. Unfortunately I can not listen to music at
work... Sucks but it is the price I pay for working at a law firm.

there is no way for me to get to Miami at this time. Once a year Area 33
broadcasts live from the WMC... I heard one of the Dj's talking about some
mix contests coming up on Beatport with web submissions and they were
talking about parties at Space and the Ultra Party music fest and all this
other shit.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Nrr: XM-Sirius merger approved by DOJ + WMC STREAM!



Are you deliberately being obtuse for the humor value? :)

Consider it this way.  A crackhead is standing in front of 222 Hyde
screaming his head off randomly.  Can you hear him?

If you're nowhere near Hyde/Eddy/Turk, you're simply out of range.

If you're inside 222 and it's Techno Tuesday, it's just too loud to notice.

If you're out front grabbing a smoke, you probably can, unless you're deaf.

None of these requires the crackhead to yell AT you.  Said crackhead might
even be able to be in physical contact with you and give you his cooties
without aiming a punch at you, for that matter.

You can even be walking by and hear him, without him needing the ability
(cognitive or motor) to turn and aim his rant at you.  There's no need
to upgrade the crackhead, you just have to make yourself ready to hear.



On Wed, Mar 26, 2008 at 09:02:32PM -0700, Sarilion wrote:
> how does a receiver receive if it's not being hit?  LOL
> 
> 
> sarilion
> 
> At 08:02 PM 3/26/2008, you wrote:
> 
> >Well, there are upgrades in terms of software, but how satellites work is
> >pretty well known to the engineers that do stuff with em.
> >
> >Satts don't "hit" moving targets, they simply hit a given coverage zone
> >(a kidney shaped contour for a given power level).  It's not that the GPS
> >birds hit the receivers so much as the receivers are designed to track
> >satellites as the receiver moves.  The same thing works for media in the
> >form of the Satellite TV that some airlines offer on planes.  It just costs
> >more as the tracking has to get more responsive.  That dish used for home
> >is the cheap way since the house doesn't move relative to the satellite,
> >but marine receivers have long since been in the "affordable" range that
> >could handle it, and yes, there are the XM/Sirius type receivers that do
> >something similar, but it's all in the receiving equipment regardless.
> >
> >The real innovation that makes things possible is changes in signal 
> >encoding
> >to make more efficient use of the bandwidth.  Traditional C-band gives way
> >to Ku-Band, 4PSK and then 8PSK improve things further.  Many options to
> >"compress" the stream to fit into a smaller data stream, with only minimal
> >changes in the big birds themselves up in orbit.
> >
> >
> >ray
> >
> >
> >
> >On Wed, Mar 26, 2008 at 06:24:29PM -0700, Sarilion wrote:
> >> you can't upgrade a satellite..
> >>
> >> I'm not aware of any geosynchronous satellite networks that have the
> >> correct tech to hit moving targets, except for GPS?
> >>
> >>
> >> sarilion

Subject: Re: [sfraves] salvia divinorum

Extract is supposed to be very potent (2x, 4x, etc.) regular leaf is  
not. Be very careful. Salvia is very powerful and disorienting. Have  
a sitter. If you're going to be alone, put a note on your door that  
says: "you are tripping, stay inside!"

do a google search for "d m turner salvia" and download the book from  
one of the torrent links.

On Mar 26, 2008, at 10:07 PM, Ray Wong wrote:

>
>
> Are you deliberately being obtuse for the humor value? :)
>
> Consider it this way.  A crackhead is standing in front of 222 Hyde
> screaming his head off randomly.  Can you hear him?
>
> If you're nowhere near Hyde/Eddy/Turk, you're simply out of range.
>
> If you're inside 222 and it's Techno Tuesday, it's just too loud to  
> notice.
>
> If you're out front grabbing a smoke, you probably can, unless  
> you're deaf.
>
> None of these requires the crackhead to yell AT you.  Said crackhead  
> might
> even be able to be in physical contact with you and give you his  
> cooties
> without aiming a punch at you, for that matter.
>
> You can even be walking by and hear him, without him needing the  
> ability
> (cognitive or motor) to turn and aim his rant at you.  There's no need
> to upgrade the crackhead, you just have to make yourself ready to  
> hear.
>
>
>
> On Wed, Mar 26, 2008 at 09:02:32PM -0700, Sarilion wrote:
>> how does a receiver receive if it's not being hit?  LOL
>>
>>
>> sarilion
>>
>> At 08:02 PM 3/26/2008, you wrote:
>>
>>> Well, there are upgrades in terms of software, but how satellites  
>>> work is
>>> pretty well known to the engineers that do stuff with em.
>>>
>>> Satts don't "hit" moving targets, they simply hit a given coverage  
>>> zone
>>> (a kidney shaped contour for a given power level).  It's not that  
>>> the GPS
>>> birds hit the receivers so much as the receivers are designed to  
>>> track
>>> satellites as the receiver moves.  The same thing works for media  
>>> in the
>>> form of the Satellite TV that some airlines offer on planes.  It  
>>> just costs
>>> more as the tracking has to get more responsive.  That dish used  
>>> for home
>>> is the cheap way since the house doesn't move relative to the  
>>> satellite,
>>> but marine receivers have long since been in the "affordable"  
>>> range that
>>> could handle it, and yes, there are the XM/Sirius type receivers  
>>> that do
>>> something similar, but it's all in the receiving equipment  
>>> regardless.
>>>
>>> The real innovation that makes things possible is changes in signal
>>> encoding
>>> to make more efficient use of the bandwidth.  Traditional C-band  
>>> gives way
>>> to Ku-Band, 4PSK and then 8PSK improve things further.  Many  
>>> options to
>>> "compress" the stream to fit into a smaller data stream, with only  
>>> minimal
>>> changes in the big birds themselves up in orbit.
>>>
>>>
>>> ray
>>>
>>>
>>>
>>> On Wed, Mar 26, 2008 at 06:24:29PM -0700, Sarilion wrote:

>>>>
>>>> I'm not aware of any geosynchronous satellite networks that have  
>>>> the

>>>>
>>>>

>>>> options to

>Consider it this way.  A crackhead is standing in front of 222 Hyde
>screaming his head off randomly.  Can you hear him?
>
>If you're nowhere near Hyde/Eddy/Turk, you're simply out of range.
>
>If you're inside 222 and it's Techno Tuesday, it's just too loud to notice.
>
>If you're out front grabbing a smoke, you probably can, unless you're deaf.
>
>None of these requires the crackhead to yell AT you.  Said crackhead might
>even be able to be in physical contact with you and give you his cooties
>without aiming a punch at you, for that matter.
>
>You can even be walking by and hear him, without him needing the ability
>(cognitive or motor) to turn and aim his rant at you.  There's no need
>to upgrade the crackhead, you just have to make yourself ready to hear.
>
>
>
>On Wed, Mar 26, 2008 at 09:02:32PM -0700, Sarilion wrote:
> > how does a receiver receive if it's not being hit?  LOL
> >
> >
> > sarilion
> >
> > At 08:02 PM 3/26/2008, you wrote:
> >
> > >Well, there are upgrades in terms of software, but how satellites work is
> > >pretty well known to the engineers that do stuff with em.
> > >
> > >Satts don't "hit" moving targets, they simply hit a given coverage zone
> > >(a kidney shaped contour for a given power level).  It's not that the GPS
> > >birds hit the receivers so much as the receivers are designed to track
> > >satellites as the receiver moves.  The same thing works for media in the
> > >form of the Satellite TV that some airlines offer on planes.  It 
> just costs
> > >more as the tracking has to get more responsive.  That dish used for home
> > >is the cheap way since the house doesn't move relative to the satellite,
> > >but marine receivers have long since been in the "affordable" range that
> > >could handle it, and yes, there are the XM/Sirius type receivers that do
> > >something similar, but it's all in the receiving equipment regardless.
> > >
> > >The real innovation that makes things possible is changes in signal
> > >encoding
> > >to make more efficient use of the bandwidth.  Traditional C-band gives way
> > >to Ku-Band, 4PSK and then 8PSK improve things further.  Many options to
> > >"compress" the stream to fit into a smaller data stream, with only minimal
> > >changes in the big birds themselves up in orbit.
> > >
> > >
> > >ray
> > >
> > >
> > >

It's definitely a powerful and disorienting psychedelic.  My 2-3 experiences
smoking it were all good, but many of my friends have felt the terror that
the saliva world they were trapped in, would go on until the end of time.
It's best to be smoked out of a bong, because the smoke is really, really
harsh.  I think the stuff I smoked was like 30x or 40x.  I wouldn't mind
trying 50x.  While I'm not Jerry Garcia, this is the one hallucinogen that
really seems to have the potential for an out of body experience, so be
prepared for the insane.

MIME-Version: 1.0

Message-ID: <429934.21214.qm@web32401.mail.mud.yahoo.com>
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] salvia divinorum

I've never taken salvia, but one person I know that did described it as disorienting and disturbing.  He said he wouldn't take it again or recommend it.  Of course he also took it alone in a hotel room in Amsterdam after smoking vast amounts of weed over a three day period.

As with any psychedelic substance, IMO, you should first educate yourself (http://www.erowid.org/plants/salvia/salvia.shtml) and then ask yourself honestly why you are taking the plant/chemical and what you hope to learn or understand through the experience.  I've found that simply considering the desired outcome is a very useful guide to making decisions about taking mind altering substances.  I've even started doing this for alcohol and caffeine.  Often when I carefully consider my real purpose these days I end up going for a walk instead of getting that double espresso or whatever.  

Especially if you take larger doses of any of these substances you should not treat it as a "recreational" experience. Treat these substances carefully and take the experience seriously.  Consider set and setting  (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_and_setting)   

Having a safe location and sober sitter is always recommended for any unfamiliar substance especially since different people may respond very differently to the same dosage.  

YMMV.

Best,

Peter

one of the torrent links.

Cable Recordings and Shine present:

*~*CABLE WEDNESDAYS*~*

Every 2nd and 4th Wednesday @ SHINE
9pm - 2am
21+

funkysleazydirtygroovybanginspacediscohouseandbreaks

03/26/08 Edition:

Special Guest DJ's:
Formless (Flytrap / Day of Hugs / Bete Noire - UK)

Dan Jones is a London based DJ and producer with a long-standing passion for 
underground house music. Djing and producing under the name Formless, he has 
been rocking clubs around London with a blend of forward thinking tech house 
and dirty electro beats.
In the last 12 months he has been creating a buzz with his unique, 
energetic, upfront sound at respected London venues like The Cross, 
Turnmills, Pacha, The Key and The Island. His brisk ascent through the DJ 
ranks came on the back of a number of DJ mix competition wins and playing a 
live set on MoS Radio. This gave the exposure needed to push his sound onto 
bigger dancefloors. Having consolidated his position in London, Formless is 
now taking his music to the international club scene.

With more dates in San Francisco, Sydney, Brisbane and the Ukraine on the 
horizon, time in the studio working on a new solo EP and a number of remixes 
and collaborations, the future looks bright for one of djing's freshest 
talents. On top of DJ and production commitments Dan has just launched his 
own night Flytrap, already hosting parties at The Cross, The Island & Pacha 
London. He still finds time every summer to co-ordinate the music for the 
Norgstock Festival (nr. Stonehenge) and run his own Day of Hugs bi-annual 
Manor House Party (nr. Bournemouth).

also playing:

The Vinyl Whore (High On Hope - SF)

w/ Residents:
Justin Johnson (Cable Recordings / Barely Legal Records / Kingsize-USA - 
NYC/SF)
Marc(O) (OtherWorld / Cable Wednesdays / The MidnightSons - DC/SF )

NO COVER!!!!
2 for 1 Smirnoff drinks!!!!
Free photo booth from FLICKR!!!!!

SHINE is located at:
1337 Mission Street (between 9th & 10th)
San Francisco, CA 94103
415-255-1337

    DJ Dan's - Attribute to James Brown???

Damn that boy played some funky ass breaks back in the day.  I just got 
a hold of a bunch of old Dan mixes and it's amazing how commercializing 
really takes the creativity out of their music.  He played such a range 
of genres and played them all so well, but now when i see or hear him 
his music is all bland and thrown together.  Same with all the other big 
DJ's too.  So so sad...Thank god people have really started archiving 
their old music and all new dj's are being archived as they go, so you 
can always enjoy a DJ when they were in their prime.

> >even be able to be in physical contact with you and give you his cooties
> >without aiming a punch at you, for that matter.
> >
> >You can even be walking by and hear him, without him needing the ability
> >(cognitive or motor) to turn and aim his rant at you.  There's no need
> >to upgrade the crackhead, you just have to make yourself ready to hear.

> >On Wed, Mar 26, 2008 at 09:02:32PM -0700, Sarilion wrote:
> >> how does a receiver receive if it's not being hit?  LOL
> >>
> >>
> >> sarilion
> >>
> >> At 08:02 PM 3/26/2008, you wrote:
> >>
> >> >Well, there are upgrades in terms of software, but how satellites work 
> >is
> >> >pretty well known to the engineers that do stuff with em.
> >> >
> >> >Satts don't "hit" moving targets, they simply hit a given coverage zone
> >> >(a kidney shaped contour for a given power level).  It's not that the 
> >GPS
> >> >birds hit the receivers so much as the receivers are designed to track
> >> >satellites as the receiver moves.  The same thing works for media in the
> >> >form of the Satellite TV that some airlines offer on planes.  It 
> >just costs
> >> >more as the tracking has to get more responsive.  That dish used for 
> >home
> >> >is the cheap way since the house doesn't move relative to the satellite,
> >> >but marine receivers have long since been in the "affordable" range that
> >> >could handle it, and yes, there are the XM/Sirius type receivers that do
> >> >something similar, but it's all in the receiving equipment regardless.
> >> >
> >> >The real innovation that makes things possible is changes in signal
> >> >encoding
> >> >to make more efficient use of the bandwidth.  Traditional C-band gives 
> >way
> >> >to Ku-Band, 4PSK and then 8PSK improve things further.  Many options to
> >> >"compress" the stream to fit into a smaller data stream, with only 
> >minimal
> >> >changes in the big birds themselves up in orbit.
> >> >
> >> >
> >> >ray
> >> >
> >> >
> >> >
> >> >On Wed, Mar 26, 2008 at 06:24:29PM -0700, Sarilion wrote:

Subject: Re: [sfraves] salvia divinorum

i tried it a couple years ago and its definitely not "weak".

i bought i think the 10x stuff, hit it out of a bong (yeah, the smoke
is harsh and smells kinda gross), and honestly wasn't expecting much,
as it was sold over the counter at smoke shops.

the next thing i know i was really disoriented, confused about what
had happened/where i was/how i got there, and things felt "weird", in
an uncomfortable kind of way.  things looked strange and kind of
electric, borders became jagged in a harsh and uglyish way (i had
feelings/images of comb teeth), and i felt like there was this
twisting kind of "torque" pressure all around me.  i had my "sitter"
(the person not fucked up) take the pipe from me cuz i felt like it
was going to break in my hand from the twisting force.  weird, i know.

after several seconds, eventually i kinda remembered "oh yeah, you're
fucked up on some weird drug" and from there i was more able to just
kind of observe, knowing its effects would subside shortly.
ultimately, the feeling was intriguing but kind of
disturbing/uncomfortable, and i was looking forward to coming down.  i
tried it a couple more times that week (there was still some left) out
of continued curiosity or to have other people try it with me and get
their reactions.  everyone generally found it "interesting" but no one
would really say they "liked" it.  the one thing many people can agree
upon tho, is that its alot more powerful and mind-bending than they
were expecting!  i'd see the abuse potential of this drug as being
very low, due mostly to the fact that its not exactly "fun". i can't
name a single person who's tried it and has went on to become a
regular user of the stuff.

it is most definitely "interesting" tho, and if you're a fan of
exploring altered states of consciousness from a sort of "research"
perspective (as i am), i'd say its worth trying once or twice just for
the experience.  thankfully it doesnt last too long.

if you're looking for a good time tho, i'd say skip it.  i doubt i'll
ever try it again.


now, dmt on the other hand.....   ;)


-------> gb

Follow up to an earlier email story...=20
=20
L.A. Times Apologizes for Shakur Story
March 27, 2008, 6:12 AM EST
=20
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Times apologized for using documents th=
at were apparently fabricated in a story implicating associates of Sean "Di=
ddy" Combs in a 1994 assault on rapper Tupac Shakur.
=20
"The bottom line is that the documents we relied on should not have been us=
ed," Editor Russ Stanton said in a story posted Wednesday night on the news=
paper's Web site. "We apologize both to our readers and to those referenced=
 in the documents ... and in the story."

Follow up to an earlier email story...

L.A. Times Apologizes for Shakur Story
March 27, 2008, 6:12 AM EST

LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Times apologized for using documents 
that were apparently fabricated in a story implicating associates of Sean 
"Diddy" Combs in a 1994 assault on rapper Tupac Shakur.

"The bottom line is that the documents we relied on should not have been 
used," Editor Russ Stanton said in a story posted Wednesday night on the 
newspaper's Web site. "We apologize both to our readers and to those 
referenced in the documents ... and in the story."

Subject: [sfraves] Nrr: Earth Lights out for 60 min - join me spread the word!!

I would think a city like SF would get into this but I
doubt you'll see a dent in the light of SF skyline
tomorrow eve... Anyways a good thing to do if you want
to en-rich that self karma a little :-)

http://www.earthhourus.org

On March 29, 2008 at 8 p.m., join millions of people
around the world in making a statement about climate
change by turning off your lights for Earth Hour, an
event created by the World Wildlife Fund. 

Earth Hour was created by WWF in Sydney, Australia in
2007, and in one year has grown from an event in one
city to a global movement. In 2008, millions of
people, businesses, governments and civic
organizations in nearly 200 cities around the globe
will turn out for Earth Hour. More than 100 cities
across North America will participate, including the
US flagshipsAtlanta, Chicago, Phoenix and San
Francisco and Ottawa, Montreal, Toronto and Vancouver.


We invite everyone throughout North America and around
the world to turn off the lights for an hour starting
at 8 p.m. (your own local time)whether at home or at
work, with friends and family or solo, in a big city
or a small town. 

What will you do when the lights are off? We have lots
of ideas. 

Join people all around the world in showing that you
care about our planet and want to play a part in
helping to fight climate change. Dont forget to sign
up and let us know you want to join Earth Hour. 

One hour, America. Earth Hour. Turn out for Earth
Hour! 

PS
Who's bringing out the dynamo powered sound system /
power generating dance floor for a serious dark  earth
party??? - LOL I guess drum circle would be as good as
it gets... hmmm Dolores Park anyone for a little
evening starter?

Subject: [sfraves] [BSP] Yes, Cesare vs Disorder is here TONIGHT!


Feeling left out in the cold because you couldn't go to Miami for the
WMC?  Have no fear, come drink some beer (and tip your bar staff well),
the WMC has come to SF!

You may have heard Lee Curtis or Alex Smoke playing a Cesare vs Disorder
track, even bought them on Beatport, but unless you've been hitting parties
in the London underground (a city well known for great parties) in recent
years you've likely never had the chance to hear Cesare spin live, until now.

Yes, Cesare vs Disorder has arrived for his first US visit ever!  After
his successful conference-lobby spin on Tuesday, he was shuttled about
town deep into Wednesday night to keep on cranking it out.  Now he's
bringing some Miami heat to Anu TONIGHT before jetting off to NYC like
the megastar he is.  Combined with our own versatile and consistent DJ
SAYAKA, this is the hot party and your chance to see what the early
conference buzz was all about.


Friday, 28 March, 2008

RAY presents: 

F A K T I O N : because san francisco needs another techno cult
with special guests and extended sets:

Friday, 28 March 2008:
Cesare vs Disorder - MEAN,KALIMARI,STOCK 5,STHLM [ Italy|UK ] 
DJ SAYAKA - BABD/Faktion [ Japan|San Francisco ]

Last Fridays @ Anu

Cesare vs Disorder:
London based, Italian born DJ, music producer, creative Cesare Marchese aka
Cesare vs Disorder (also "Queen AtOm") has been involved in the european
underground music scene for the last 10 years.  His skills and passion for
DJing has taken him around Italy, to Berlin, Poland, Finland, Switzerland,
Brazil, and of course his current home in the UK, where he continues to
also produce, having formed EssentialReload and newborn labels MEAN and
SERIALISM.

This is Cesare vs Disorder's ONLY scheduled West Coast appearance before
he returns to London, nestled in between his appearances in Miami and NYC.
Don't miss out!

DJ SAYAKA is known around the world for her consistent mastery of always
difficult downtempo, medodic techno, flawless track track selection and
natural progression.  Recently returned from her own globe-trecking gigs,
including NYC and Tokyo, it's our good fortune she's called San Francisco
home since 2004.


Anu-Bar 
43 Sixth St., San Francisco, CA
10 PM to 2 AM 21+
Cost: $5, free before 11pm

Official Site: http://www.faktionsf.com/

Can't wait til 10pm for your techno to start?  Our friends Killswitch are
at UndergroundSF tonight for happy hour goodness from 6pm-10pm, the perfect
time to show up at Anu!

 
///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
 
Coming up: Faktion: Last Fridays @ Anu 
Friday, 25 April 2008:
DJ DRAGN'FLY: DJ4NORML/DJDRAGNFLY.COM [ SAC/SF ]
DJ AMBER: Sister SF/iamthedj.com [ SF ]

Meister Brau was a nasty cheap beer from Miller back in the day, don't
think they make it anymore.  Come to think of it however, I think the
original brewery called Meister Brau (Miller bought the company for
the name/label) had a light beer which lives on as Miller Lite, but
the full on undiluted stuff is gone.

Let's not forget Lucky Lager and Schaeffer.  Schaeffer isn't really beer tho, its sort of a watery beer substitute.  Its the processed cheese food of beer.

Lucky Lager had rebuses in the cap too BTW.

The pizza place I used to work at in high school used to sell Michelob Dark on tap.  I don't think it was really dark beer so much as Michelob that was accidentally colored wrong.  That was some fine drinking.  My partner in crime at the time and I drank more of one keg than the customers leading the owners to ban employees drinking on the job.  We quit shortly thereafter.

From: <dangrsmind@yahoo.com>
To: "Terry Estioko" <terry@hyperreal.org>; "Phillip Mispagel" 
<phillip@viberation.com>
Cc: "stoney_penny" <stoney_penny@yahoo.com>; "Ray Wong" <rayw@rayw.net>;

Sent: Monday, March 31, 2008 7:43 AM
Subject: Re: [sfraves] oh moh-kshaaaa


Some of the sickest visuals I've seen you guys do Terry...

I especially enjoyed the bit that was sort of mathematical formulas (ok I'm 
a math nerd)  and then there was a dna strand rotating as well.  Oh and also 
the game footage with the sort of punk night club scene.  That was totally 
perfect.

I got to the party early and also heard Andy W. vs Chris Jackson...some 
great techno that was excellently complimented by the visuals.  But it was 
still  pretty early and there weren't that many people on the dance floor 
yet...

I kept wandering into the small side room as well.  Was that Brian B. that 
opened?  I tried to circle back and introduce myself if it was, but he was 
gone and I never found him again.  Ah well.

Someone (DV8?) played a great dirty house set after Bam's breaks that was 
just what the Doctor ordered.  The sound in that little room was kicking, 
especially in this one spot on the left whjer ehte bass was coming through 
the floor just right...

Then I was back out in the main room for Dragn'fly and Forest Green's 
excellent sets.  I ran out of steam around 2:30 and headed for the door.

I saw Osby and Marco briefly, Agent Smith and his beautiful and brilliant 
wife, and of course Terry.  Didn't meet any new peeps from the list, but I 
did meet some cool folks from other walks of life.  I spent a good amount of 
time talking with another Peter and his girlfriend S. from Saratoga as well 
Finney from UCB.  I had a nice talk with Rob from Moksha Tribe while he was 
working the hooka room as well.  It was good to see the vibe fresh in so 
many younger kids, although I got a bit worried about S later in the evening 
as she was getting a little spaced.

I never saw Adriana tho...did you make it?  Hope that worked out.

Great party, great venue as always (a lighter in the vending machine, thank 
you!) , and great people.  Only negative: the kitchen ran out of red bull at 
around 2AM, forcing me to remember why I hate drinking Coca Cola at parties.

Best,

Peter

> room was kicking, especially in this one spot on the left whjer

From: Dragn'fly [mailto:dragnfly@djdragnfly.com]
Sent: Sunday, March 30, 2008 9:23 AM
To: 'SFR'
Subject: [sfraves] oh moh-kshaaaa

I thought I'd won my 2 week battle with that friggin flu bug, but I got a
huge wakeup call when I got hit with the sickness again this weekend.
It got so bad Saturday, that by midnight, I seriously didn't think I'd be
able to make it to the party and I was BUMMIN' BIG TIME!  Near midnight, I'd
pretty much resigned to the fact that I'd most likely have to count myself
out, but at the very last possible minute, I sucked it up and said fuck and
on the road we went. In the end I figured if I'm gonna die, it may as well
be in the company of a lot of my longtime favorite folks.  To make a
potentially long story short (mostly 'cause the Nyquil I just slammed is now
just starting to kick it), I'm just fucking glad I was able to cowboy up and
make the trip.  It was well worth the sweat to get down there and in the
end, I think some of you even helped with out with your reiki ways.  Thanks
a mucho for that. 
 
So what I'm trying to say in all this blabberlike jibberish is that I had
ended up having a great time (so did Terri) and it was great to see you
crazy mofos again! (too damn many I ain't seen in years!) 

Moksha rocks my locks!
 
PS - Chris Jackson is a "whore" !!!!  (he he he)
 
Off to bed I go!
 
; )
d

crowd.  The rave scene in this area was started by a bunch of tech geeks who
are now in their early 30s to mid 40s and still party regularly.
